# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1948-summer-olympics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] On 15 February 2003, a coordinated day of protests was held across the world in which people in more than 600 cities expressed opposition to the imminent Iraq War.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] It was part of a series of protests and political events that had begun in 2002 and continued as the invasion, war, and occupation took place.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The day was described by social movement researchers as "the largest protest event in human history".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] According to BBC News, between six and ten million people took part in protests in up to sixty countries over the weekend of 15 and 16 February.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The largest protests took place in Europe.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The one in Rome involved around three million people, and is listed in the 2004 *Guinness Book of World Records* as the largest anti-war rally in history.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Madrid hosted the second largest rally with more than 1.5 million people protesting against the invasion of Iraq.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Beijing, three smaller protests were held the following day, attended by foreigners and domestic students.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In 2002, the United States government began to argue for the necessity of invading Iraq.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This formally began with a speech by US President George W.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Bush to the United Nations General Assembly on 12 September 2002 which argued that the Iraqi government of Saddam Hussein was violating United Nations (UN) resolutions, primarily on weapons of mass destruction, and that this necessitated action.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The proposed war was controversial with many people questioning the motives of the US government and its rationale.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] One poll which covered 41 countries claimed that less than 10% would support an invasion of Iraq without UN sanction and that half would not support an invasion under any circumstances.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Anti-war groups worldwide organised public protests.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] According to the French academic Dominique Reynié, between 3 January and 12 April 2003, 36 million people across the globe took part in almost 3,000 anti‑war protests, the demonstrations on 15 February 2003 being the largest and most prolific.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The 15 February international protests were unprecedented not only in terms of the size of the demonstrations but also in terms of the international coordination involved.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Immanuel Wallerstein has spoken of the international protests as being organised by the forces of "the camps of Porto Alegre and Davos" in reference to the emergence of global social movements who had been organising around international events such as the 2001 World Social Forum in Porto Alegre.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The idea for an international day of demonstrations was first raised by the British anti-capitalist group Globalise Resistance (GR) in the wake of an anti-war demonstration in Britain of 400,000 on 28 September.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] At the time GR was involved in planning for the Florence European Social Forum (ESF) and brought up the suggestion at an ESF planning meeting.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] According to GR's Chris Nineham, "There was considerable controversy.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Some delegates were worried it would alienate the mainstream of the movement.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The proposal was accepted and at the final rally of the ESF, in November 2002, the call officially went out for Europe-wide demonstrations on 15 February 2003.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This call was firmed up in December at a planning meeting for the following ESF which took place in Copenhagen in 2003.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This meeting was attended by delegates from many European anti-war organisations, the US group United for Peace and Justice, and representatives of groups from the Philippines.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The decision was taken to set up a Europe-wide anti-war website and to commit to spreading organisational coordination both within and beyond Europe.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] An email network connecting the different national organisations across Europe, and eventually also the different US groups, was set up.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In December 2002, the Cairo Anti-war Conference pledged to organize demonstrations in Egypt and the International Campaign Against Aggression on Iraq (which came out of the Cairo conference) sought to co-ordinate more demonstrations across the world.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Around this time, the US anti-war group International ANSWER called for actions in North America supporting the proposed protests in Europe.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Another important platform for the spreading call to demonstrate internationally occurred at the World Social Forum in Porto Alegre, Brazil which took place at the end of 2002.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] European delegates sought to popularize the plan for the increasingly international demonstration.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] They met with some success, including the organisation of an anti‑war assembly which was attended by almost 1,000 people.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The song "Boom!", by System of a Down, had a music video filmed on the day of the protest, showing the many protest locations and people's opinions on the Iraq War.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Demonstrations took place across Europe and some of the largest drawing attendance figures in the tens of thousands in many cities.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Approximately one-fifth of the total demonstrators worldwide protested in Europe.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Austria, 30,000 people (SW estimate) took to the streets of its capital, Vienna.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Switzerland in order to "concentrate the movement" most activists agreed to organise a single demonstration for the whole country in Bern.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] On the day roughly 40,000 people joined the protest in front of the Bundeshaus, the seat of the Swiss federal government and parliament.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The demonstration, which ran under the slogan **Nein zum Krieg gegen Irak – Kein Blut für Öl!** (No to war in Iraq – no blood for oil!) was the largest in Switzerland since 1945.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Slovenia, roughly 3,000 people gathered in Ljubljana's central park of Congress Square, supported by the mayor Danica Simšič, and marched the streets in one of the largest demonstrations since independence in 1991.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Benelux countries had large demonstrations for their total population size.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Belgium organisers had expected around 30,000 people to attend a demonstration in Brussels, which is the home of the European Parliament.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] They were shocked by a turn out of approximately 100,000 people (WSWS and GLW estimate).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The march took over 3 hours to cross the city.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Netherlands saw around 70,000 (*USA Today* estimate) to 75,000 people (WSWS estimate) protest in Amsterdam.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This was the country's largest demonstration since the anti-nuclear campaigns of the 1980s.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Anti war website antiwar.com reports that 8,000-14,000 people were present at protests in Luxembourg, however they do not provide a citation for this figure.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Bosnia and Herzegovina saw around 100 protesters gather in Mostar.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This protest spanned the sectarian divide with both Bosniaks and Croats attending.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There were also protests in Croatia where 10,000 people (WSWS estimate) took part in a protest in the capital city of Zagreb.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Croatia also saw protests in Osijek, Vukovar, Knin, Zadar, Šibenik, Split and Dubrovnik.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Cyprus saw a demonstration of between 500 (*USA Today* estimate) and more than 800 people (SW estimate) at the British army base in Dhekelia.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Enduring heavy rain protesters briefly blocked the base.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] They then marched to Pyla village where they watched other demonstrations occurring across the world on a giant screen.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The demonstration was mostly attended by Greek Cypriots but they were joined by some Turkish Cypriots.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In the Czech Republic, over 1,000 people joined a rally at Jan Palach Square in Prague.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Czech philosopher Erazim Kohak addressed the crowd, saying, "War is not a solution, war is a problem." Protesters listened to music and speeches before marching to the Czech government building, where they submitted petitions, then march continued to the US embassy.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In France, there were demonstrations in somewhere between twenty (*Observer* estimate) and eighty cities (WSWS estimate); the organisers estimated that over half a million marched in total.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The biggest demonstration took place in Paris, where around 100,000 (*USA Today* estimate) to 200,000 (WSWS estimate) people marched through the streets, ending in a rally at the Place de la Bastille.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This location's role in the French Revolution was considered to give it a historical significance.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There was also a demonstration in Toulouse of around 10,000 people.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Germany, coaches brought people from over 300 German towns to Berlin to join a demonstration of 300,000 (police estimate) to 500,000 (organizers' estimate) people; the largest demonstration that had occurred in Berlin for several decades.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protesters, including members of Gerhard Schröder's government, filled the boulevard between the Brandenburg Gate and the Victory Column.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Athens, Greece, 150,000 people (WSWS estimate) demonstrated.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The protest was generally peaceful, but a small group clashed with police.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The police fired tear gas at the group some of whom threw rocks and petrol bombs.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Police reported that the trouble was down to a group of anarchists who had split off from the main demonstration.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Ireland, the Dublin march was only expected to draw 20,000 people, but the actual figure was given variously as 80,000 (police estimate), 90,000 (BBC estimate), 100,000 (*Guardian* estimate) or 150,000 (Socialist Worker (SW) estimate).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The march went from Parnell Square, passing the Department of Foreign Affairs at St.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Stephen's Green, and on to the Dame Street for a rally where popular Irish folk singer Christy Moore, Kíla and Labour Party politician Michael D.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Higgins were among many speakers from the platform.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The march disrupted traffic for more than four hours.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protesters demanded that the Irish government stop allowing the United States military to use Ireland's Shannon Airport as a transatlantic stop-off point in bringing soldiers to the Middle East.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The biggest demonstration of the global day of protest took place in Italy in Rome.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Nearly 3,000 buses and thirty trains were specially chartered to bring people to the demonstration, which was organised under the slogan "Stop the war; no ifs or buts".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The organisers were shocked at the size of the turn out and the unexpected number of people forced the demonstration to set off two hours early.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The size of the demonstration meant that the majority of demonstrators did not make it into the final rally and in total three million people (organisers' estimate, supported by the Guinness Book of World Records) were on the streets.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This was listed in the 2004 Guinness Book of World Records as the largest anti-war rally in history.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] According to the *Green Left Weekly* (GLW), the demonstration contained people from across Italian society; "Catholic nuns and priests marched alongside young people with dreadlocks, nose rings and Palestinian scarves.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Christians, anarchists and communists mingled".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Approximately 1,000 demonstrated (SW estimate) in Malta.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] After the demonstration an anti-war concert was held in the capital, Valletta.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Norway saw its biggest series of protests since 1917.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The biggest took place in its capital Oslo were more than 60,000 protesters (Police estimate and Socialist Worker estimate) joining a demonstration.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protests of around 15,000 took place in Bergen and Trondheim, and 10,000 in Stavanger.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Small protests also took place in at least 30 towns across the country.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] At the rally in Oslo the vice-chair of the Norwegian Confederation of Trade Unions (LO) spoke from the platform claiming that "Bush only cares about American oil interests".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Denmark 20,000 to 30,000 protesters (WSWS estimate) took part in a march in the capital city, Copenhagen.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Sweden, 35,000 demonstrated in Stockholm. and about 25,000 in Gothenburg.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Helsinki, Finland, an estimated 15,000 people participated in one of the largest mass-protests in the republic's history.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There was a demonstration in Warsaw, Poland of 10,000 people (SW estimate).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The demonstration through central Warsaw passed the US embassy.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Another protest, organized by the local Wrocław Anti-War Coalition (WKA), was held in the city of Wrocław in the market square by the town hall, with 400–500 people participating.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Lisbon, police estimated that around 35,000 people gathered to march through the city.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Three former Portuguese prime ministers were in attendance.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Russia, which had several demonstrations, the largest occurred in Moscow, with 200,000 people (WSWS estimate) in attendance.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Small demonstrations also took place in Serbia, where there was a demonstration of 200 people (WSWS estimate) in the capital city of Belgrade.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] It was estimated that 1,000 people marched in the capital of Slovakia, Bratislava.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Barcelona also had a large, with estimates of 350,000 (Delegación de Gobierno), 1,300,000 (Barcelona city hall and Police) or 1,500,000 (GLW) people joining a demonstration which moved from the Passeig de Gràcia to the Plaça de Tetuan.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The city of Oviedo had a population of 180,000 and a turnout of 100,000.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The main demonstration in Turkey took place in Istanbul, thousands (SW estimate) demonstrated.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The local authorities had banned the protest claiming to have worries about national security, however the protest organisers went ahead with the rally under the cover of calling a press conference.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There were also demonstrations in Adana, Ankara, İzmir, Zonguldak, İzmit, Antalya and Muğla.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There was also a demonstration in Ukraine of around 2,000 people (*USA Today* estimate) joined a "Rock against the war" rally in Kyiv's central square.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In the lead-up to 15 February, the Stop the War Coalition was organising the march from a small office donated by the National Association of Teachers in Further and Higher Education.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] They planned for the two marches to merge at Piccadilly Circus and then proceed to a rally at Hyde Park.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The negotiations for this plan faltered when the Labour government's Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport Tessa Jowell initially instructed the Royal Parks agency to deny permission for the rally in Hyde Park for safety reasons and to protect the grass.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Trafalgar Square was suggested by Jowell as the alternative venue, but the Mayor of London Ken Livingstone insisted it was of insufficient size.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The government's decision was reversed by 5 February.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Sections of the media supported this demonstration.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The *Daily Mirror* gave large coverage in the lead up to the march and provided thousands of placards on the day.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The demonstration also received sponsorship support from Greenpeace and Mecca-Cola.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] As the date for the march approached the BBC was predicting that around 500,000 people would attend, while StWC was hoping for numbers to top the symbolically significant million mark.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The British Stop the War Coalition (Stop) claimed the protest in London was the largest political demonstration in the city's history.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Police estimated attendance as well in excess of 750,000 people and the BBC estimated that around a million attended.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The weather, on the day of the protest was grey and cold, but reports noted that people remained "in high spirits" as London became gridlocked and protesters were stuck for hours at Gower Street and the Embankment, the two starting points for the march.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The police began the march earlier than intended on safety grounds because of the number of people who had arrived in central London.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Hundreds of coaches brought protesters from 250 towns and cities across the UK, with around 100 coaches coming from Wales alone.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Many commentators noted the diversity of those attending the march.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] All police leave in the capital was cancelled for the event, though Scotland Yard later said that it passed off almost without incident.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protesters who managed to reach Hyde Park in time heard various speakers, including Harold Pinter, George Galloway, Tony Benn and Bianca Jagger however many were not able to reach the rally as those travelling home by coach had to leave before completing the march route.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protesters at the back end of the march did not reach Hyde Park until hours after the speakers and performers had finished.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Charles Kennedy, then the leader of the Liberal Democrats, was a late addition to the list of speakers.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There was some media speculation that he only decided to speak after a lead article in *The Guardian* was critical of his absence from the planned speaker list.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Because of the size of the march, accurate estimates of the number of people in attendance are difficult.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] It is relatively uncontentious that the march was the largest ever political demonstration in the UK and the biggest taking to the streets since the Golden Jubilee weekend in 2002.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In an ICM poll for *The Guardian* (14 February 2003 – 16 February 2003), 6% of people claimed that someone from their household went on the march or had intended to.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Stop claims that this translates into 1.25 million households and thus supports the estimate of two million people, assuming that more than one person could come from each household.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] RadioVague in conjunction with the now defunct CableRadio broadcast speeches, music and interviews from the event to the internet throughout the day using a satellite uplink provided by Psand.net.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] A sole person demonstrated in opposition to the march outside the Iraqi section of the Jordanian Embassy on the day – Jacques More a writer from Croydon – with a placard saying that, although a last resort, war is necessary "[w]hen evil dictators rule and murder their own people".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Ten years on writer Ian Sinclair assembled an oral history of the demonstration.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Journalist Ellie Mae O'Hagan, a UK Uncut activist, told Sinclair that despite its size "it did absolutely nothing".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Other witnesses, such as Milan Rai, are of the opposite opinion: "We achieved a lot, and a hell of a lot more than we realise".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Tariq Ali, one of the speakers in February 2003, said at the tenth anniversary: "I didn't quite tell them 'Blair is going to go to war regardless of today' but I knew that".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] "It was a huge show of anger but that's about it.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] "One demonstration never overturned government policy overnight – or very rarely – and on something as strategic and massive as that", commented Seumas Milne in an interview with *The Quietus* online magazine in October 2012.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In addition to the demonstrations in England, the United Kingdom also saw protests in Scotland.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Anti-war activists planned a demonstration in Glasgow which ended at the Scottish Exhibition and Conference Centre (SECC) where the Labour Party was holding a conference for party members.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Labour Party requested that the SECC refuse permission for a stage and PA system outside the conference hall.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In response to this the then Scottish Socialist Party MSP Tommy Sheridan tabled a motion in the Scottish Parliament to allow the event to take place, condemning what he claimed were attempts to "stifle all opposition to warmonger Blair".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Labour Party was unsuccessful in blocking the demonstrators' plans.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Tony Blair was due to give a speech at the same time as the protesters would have arrived outside the conference centre, but the speech was rescheduled to an earlier time to avoid this.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] On the day around 50,000 people according to the *Guardian* joined the march, which started at Glasgow Green.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] By the time the front of the march had travelled the 2 miles (3.2 km) to the SECC, Blair had delivered his speech and had left the area.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Northern Irish march was held in Belfast, where 10,000 (*Guardian* estimate) to 20,000 (SW estimate) protesters from across the sectarian divide joined the demonstration.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The march started at the Arts College at 14:30 and moved through that Royal Avenue towards Belfast City Hall.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Prominent politicians from Sinn Féin, the Social Democratic and Labour Party (SDLP) and the centrist Alliance Party joined the protest.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Sinn Féin president Gerry Adams spoke from the platform at the end rally saying "If President Bush and Mr Blair want war, it should be war against poverty and for equality." There was also a rally in Newry in County Down attending by hundreds of protesters (BBC estimate).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Canada saw protests in 70 cities and towns (WSWS estimate).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The biggest took place in Montreal where more than 100,000 people protested (SW and WSWS each estimated 150,000) despite windchill temperatures below −30 °C (−22 °F).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] 80,000 people joined a demonstration in Toronto, 40,000 in Vancouver, 18,000 (by police estimates) in Edmonton, 8,000 in Victoria, 4,000 in Halifax and 6,000 in Ottawa.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There were protests in 70 cities in total.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] These demonstrations took place despite very cold weather, average temperatures were below −35 °C (−31 °F).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Chicoutimi, 1,500 protested in windchill temperatures of −40 °C (−40 °F) wind-chill temperature in what was one of the coldest marches on that global day of protest.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protests took place all across the United States of America with CBS reporting that 150 U.S. cities had protests.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] According to the World Socialist Web Site, protests took place in 225 different communities.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The largest protests took place in the nation's largest cities including Chicago, Los Angeles, and New York City, but there were also smaller rallies in towns such as Gainesville, Georgia; Macomb, Illinois; and Juneau, Alaska, among scores of others.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Organisers of the New York City protest had hoped to march past the headquarters of the United Nations.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, a week before the march, police claimed that they would not be able to ensure order and District Court Judge Barbara Jones ruled against allowing the route.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Instead, protesters were only permitted to hold a stationary rally.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] On that day, over 300 buses and four special trains brought protesters in from across the country.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] BBC estimates that 100,000 protesters took part in a rally near the UN headquarters.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Among those taking part was the 9/11 Families For Peaceful Tomorrows, a group made up of some relatives of victims of the attacks on the World Trade Center.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Speakers included politicians, church leaders and entertainers, such as actress Susan Sarandon and South African Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] As people tried to reach the rally area they ended up constituting an unplanned march, stretching twenty blocks down First Avenue and overflowing onto Second and Third Avenue.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In total estimates range from 300,000 to 400,000 protesters (WSWS estimate).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The protests were largely peaceful though a small group of protesters who were reported to have broken off from the main rally, caused damage to property in Union Square, and threw stones at police officers, which resulted in forty arrests.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There were numerous complaints that the New York City Police Department (NYPD) were too heavy-handed.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Many streets were blocked off and protesters reported feeling hemmed in and scared.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] By the end of the day, police reported that there had been roughly 275 arrests; organisers dispute this number, claiming that there were 348 arrests.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, NYPD spokesman Michael O'Looney denied the charges claiming that the tape was "filled with special effects" and that it did not prove the police had not been provoked.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] At a demonstration in Los Angeles, California, 50,000 (WSWS estimate) to 60,000 (GLW estimate) protesters (CNN said "thousands") marched down Hollywood Boulevard filling it for four blocks.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Amongst the protesters were the actors Martin Sheen and Mike Farrell and director Rob Reiner.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Martin Sheen, who at the time was playing a fictitious U.S. president in *The West Wing*, said that "None of us can stop this war ... there is only one guy that can do that and he lives in the White House".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Other activists in California originally planned to hold a protest in San Francisco on the Saturday but they changed to the Sunday in order not to conflict with the city's Chinese New Year's parade.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The protest was held on Sunday 16 February.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The BBC estimated the crowd size to be 150,000 people, while protest organisers and police agreed that the crowd count was 200,000 people.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, a *San Francisco Chronicle* photographic investigation estimated that the number in attendance at the peak period was closer to 65,000 people, although it did not state how many people were in attendance for the duration of the demonstration.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There was some controversy over Rabbi Michael Lerner not being selected as a speaker for the rally at the end of the demonstration.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Lerner claimed that he was not picked to speak for reasons of antisemitism due to his support for the existence of the Israeli state.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Austin, Texas, 10,000 protestors marched down Congress Avenue from the state capitol building.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Colorado Springs, 4,000 protesters were dispersed with pepper spray, tear gas, stun guns and batons.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] 34 were arrested on failure to disperse and other charges and at least two protesters had to have hospital treatment.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Seattle, organisers aimed to have 20 to 30 thousand people join a march from Seattle Center following a giant blue planet, the emblem adopted by the march organisers.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] On the day 50,000 people (GLW estimate) turned out to protest under the dual slogan "Stop the war on Iraq; Stop the war on immigrants", more than on the Seattle protests against the WTO Ministerial Conference of 1999.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Demonstrations also took place in Philadelphia, where thousands (CNN estimate) joined a march to the Liberty Bell, and in Chicago, where 10,000 people demonstrated (GLW estimate).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Florida a small number of protesters staged a naked protest on Palm Beach.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] They initially had some problems getting permission for the action, but on the Thursday before, a U.S.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] District court ruled that the planned nude protest was legal at the public beach.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Most of the attendees had come from the four-day Mid-Winter Naturist Festival that was taking place at the same time.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There was also a demonstration of 900 people (*USA Today* estimate) on the island of Puerto Rico.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The chief demonstration in Mexico took place in Mexico City where around 10,000 people (*USA Today* estimate) joined a demonstration which ended with a rally at a heavily guarded US embassy.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Among the demonstrators was Nobel Peace Prize laureate Rigoberta Menchú.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protests took place across South America including Uruguay, where their protest took place on 14 February.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] An estimated 70,000 people marched down Montevideo's Avenida 18.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Brazil, a protest led by President Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva was attended by 1,500 marchers (Police estimate).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Buenos Aires, Argentina, an estimate of 50,000 protesters attended which included some veterans of the Falklands War of 1982.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Areas in Asia with large Muslim populations, in particular the countries of the West Asia, had the highest levels of opposition to the proposed Iraq war, however demonstrations in many of these countries were relatively small.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The reasons for this are complex, but one factor that is commonly cited is the suppression of protest movements by the conservative leaders of those countries.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Iraq, the country in which the war would take place, protesters marched down Palestine Street in Baghdad where several thousand Iraqis—many carrying Kalashnikov rifles—joined in the global protests.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Unlike the vast majority of protests across the world the protest in Baghdad was also in support of the Baathist regime; it was called by Saddam Hussein as "World Anger Day".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protesters carried posters of Saddam and burned US flags.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] A large protest also took place on the streets of Damascus in Syria, which borders Iraq.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protesters chanted anti-U.S. and anti-Israeli slogans while marching to the "People's Assembly" in a demonstration of between 10,000 (GLW estimate) to 200,000 protesters (CBS estimate and *USA Today* estimate).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Lebanon, 10,000 protesters (CBS, GLW estimate) took part in a demonstration in Beirut.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, the protest ended early when it rained heavily.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There were also demonstrations of 5,000 people (GLW estimate) in Amman, Jordan.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Israel there was a demonstration in Tel Aviv of approximately 2,000 (*USA Today* estimate) to 3,000 people (GLW and WSWS estimate).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The demonstration contained both Arabs and Jews.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] It was organized by a wide range of organizations including the Communist Party of Israel, the National Democratic Assembly, the Arab Democratic Party, the Independent Media Center, the Alternative Information Center, Ta'ayush, the Gush Shalom movement, and the Organization for Democratic Action.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, it was boycotted by other left-wing groups, including Peace Now and Meretz.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The demonstration was coordinated with a similar demonstration which took place in Ramallah.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Small protests took place across Japan mostly being held outside US military bases.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The biggest demonstration of the day took place in Shibuya, where 5,000 (SW estimate) people marched.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, there was a demonstration of 25,000 in Tokyo on Friday, the day before as well as smaller demonstrations in Osaka and other cities.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Tokyo protests contained Japanese veterans of World War II and survivors of the 1945 atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Around 3,000 people (SW estimate) joined an illegal demonstration in the Malaysian city of Kuala Lumpur despite police warnings that any participants in a protest would face stern action.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The demonstration ended at the US embassy at Jalan Tun Razak.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Taiwan had a protest of more than 2,000 people (WSWS estimate) in the capital city of Taipei under the slogan of "No Blood for Oil".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] India saw protests across the country including 10,000 (BBC estimate) in Calcutta.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Bangladesh 2,000 people joined a demonstration in Dhaka.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In South Korea, there was a demonstration of 2,000 people (WSWS estimate) which took place in the capital city Seoul.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The protest started with a rally at Marronnier Park after which there was a demonstration that ended in Jongmyo were the size of the protest increased in size to 3,000 people (WSWS estimate).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Jongmyo was surrounded by riot police who almost out numbered the protesters.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protests also took place in the South Korean cities of Busan, Daegu, Daejeon, Gwangju and Wonju.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Beijing, China, three protests were held the following day, attended by about 450 people in total, including foreigners and domestic students.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Johannesburg, around 8,000-10,000 people joined in a colorful and peaceful protest.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] They toyi-toyied and marched, stopping at the U.S.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Consulate General where riot police formed a protective chain around the entrance.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Cape Town 5,000 (*USA Today* estimate) to 20,000 protesters (WSWS estimate) joined a demonstration march which started at 10 in the morning on Keizersgracht road and ended at the offices of the US consulate-general which was guarded by a ring of riot police, where there was a rally with speakers.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protests were organised by the Anti-War Coalition and the Stop the War campaign of the Congress of South African Trade Unions (Cosatu).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protests of thousands of people also took place at Durban and Bloemfontein.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] A number of prominent ANC politicians attended marches.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] At the Cape Town rally the South African Minister, Pallo Jordan addressed the protesters saying; "We will stop the war.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] A protest of around 3,000 (SW estimate) in the Tunisian city of Sfax was attacked by police who beat the protesters with batons and truncheons, injuring at least 20.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protests in Fiji took place on the day before, on Friday morning, heralding the weekend of demonstrations.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protesters handed floral Valentine's Day messages to the representatives of the US, British and Australian governments urging them to avoid the war.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Friday also saw protests in Melbourne, where around 150,000 people (BBC estimate) joined a demonstration.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] On the Saturday protests also took place in Australia's national capital (Canberra), with 20,000 protesters.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Sydney demonstration on Sunday 16 February included a feeder march of 10,000 trade unionists, with 200,000 (BBC estimate) to 250,000 (Sydney Morning Herald estimate) demonstrating in Sydney.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Across the six state capitals an estimated 600,000 demonstrated in cities around the country.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Beyond the capitals, many major cities and towns around Australia had protests.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] At protests in Australia in Bellingen, New South Wales around 2,500 people (SW estimate) joined a rally at the towns sports ground.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] As well as hearing from speakers, the demonstrators were entertained by a group of a cappella singers called 'The Bushbombs'.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The rally was about as large as the town's population.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The first actual demonstration of the day took place in New Zealand where 10,000 people demonstrated in Auckland and Wellington.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Auckland march was bigger than expected, forcing police to shut off Queen Street.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] People were reported to be still starting the march as those at the front of the march reached a rally in Myers Park several kilometres away.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Wellington the march had to carry on after the then planned end point as there were too many people to fit into the park.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Around 400 to 500 people marched in Hamilton.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There were also protests in at least 18 other centres, including Dunedin, Thames, Opotiki, Whakatane, Whangarei, Timaru and Rotorua, and Picnic for Peace in Christchurch.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] A group of scientists at the US McMurdo Station held a rally on the ice at the edge of the Ross Sea.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] At the time, many commentators were hopeful that this global mobilization of unprecedented scale would stop the coming Iraq war.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] *The New York Times* writer Patrick Tyler claimed that they showed that there were "two superpowers on the planet – the United States, and worldwide public opinion".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The unprecedented size of the demonstrations was widely taken to indicate that the majority of people across the world opposed the war.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, the potential effect of the protests was generally dismissed by pro-war politicians.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Her view was borne out as the day of protests, along with the protests that followed it, failed to stop the war.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, the protests and other public opposition were seen as a key factor in the decisions of the governments of many countries, such as Canada, to not send troops to Iraq, and of Turkey to deny coalition use of airbases in its territory.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The protests have also been cited as a factor strengthening the hand of the "uncommitted six" members of the United Nations Security Council - Angola, Cameroon, Chile, Mexico, and Pakistan.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Though demonstrations against the Iraq war and subsequent occupation continued, none of the demonstrations through to 2011 matched the 15 February protest in terms of size.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] One suggested explanation for this is that people became disillusioned with marching as a political tactic because of the failure of these demonstrations to achieve their explicit aim.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In 2006, three years after the protest day, in an article arguing for people to attend a further march, Mike Marqusee put forward two counter arguments to this.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Firstly, he claimed that it was too soon to judge the long-term significance of the demonstrations.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] As examples, he stated, "People who took part in the non-cooperation campaigns in India in the 20s and 30s had to wait a long time for independence," and "There were eight years of protest and more than 2 million dead before the Vietnam war came to an end".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Secondly, he claimed that while the effect of marching may be uncertain, the effect of not marching would make it more likely that the occupation would continue.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Despite failing in its explicit aim, the 15 February global day of anti-war protests had many effects that, according to some, were not directly intended.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] According to United Kingdom left-wing anti-war activist Salma Yaqoob, one of these was that they were a powerful antidote to the idea that the war was a "Clash of Civilizations", or a religious war, an idea she claimed was propagated both by Western leaders and reactionary forces in the Arab world.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This is echoed in the words of former Hizb ut-Tahrir organiser Hadiya Masieh who said of the non-Muslims marching in London "How could we demonise people who obviously opposed aggression against Muslims?".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] A severe outbreak of cholera occurred in 1854 near Broad Street (now Broadwick Street) and Golden Square in Soho, London, England, during the worldwide 1846–1860 cholera pandemic.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The outbreak (also known as **Golden Square outbreak**), which killed 616 people, is best known for the physician John Snow's study of its causes and his hypothesis that germ-contaminated water was the cause, rather than something in the air called "miasma".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] This discovery influenced public health and the construction of improved sanitation facilities beginning in the mid-19th century.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Later, the term "focus of infection" was used to describe sites, such as the Broad Street pump, where conditions are favourable for transmission of infection.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow unknowingly took advantage of a natural experiment during his endeavours to identify the cause of cholera transmission.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] In the mid-19th century, Soho in London had a serious problem with filth due to a large influx of people and lack of proper sanitary services: the London sewer system had not reached Soho.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Cowsheds, slaughterhouses and grease-boiling dens lined the streets and contributed animal droppings, rotting fluids and other contaminants to Soho's primitive sewer system.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Many cellars had cesspools beneath their floorboards, which formed from the sewers and filth seeping in from outside.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] With the cesspools overrunning, London's government decided to dump the waste into the River Thames, contaminating the water supply.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] London had already had a "series of debilitating cholera outbreaks".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] These included outbreaks in 1832 and 1849, which killed 14,137 people.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] At the time of the Broad Street outbreak, physicians and scientists held two competing theories on the causes of cholera in the human body: miasma theory and germ theory.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The London medical community debated the cause of the city's persistent cholera outbreaks.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The cholera-causing bacterium *Vibrio cholerae* was isolated in 1854, but the finding became well known and accepted only decades later.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Miasma theorists concluded that cholera was caused by particles in the air, or "miasmata", which arose from decomposing matter or other dirty organic sources.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] "Miasma" particles were thought to travel through the air and infect individuals, and thus cause cholera.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Dr William Farr, the commissioner for the 1851 London census and a member of the General Register's Office, believed that miasma arose from the soil surrounding the River Thames.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] It contained decaying organic matter which contained miasmatic particles and was released into the London air.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Miasma theorists believed in "cleansing and scouring, rather than through the purer scientific approach of microbiology".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Farr later agreed with Snow's germ theory following Snow's publications.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] In contrast, the germ theory held that the principal cause of cholera was a germ cell that had not yet been identified.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow theorised that this unknown germ was transmitted from person to person by individuals ingesting water.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] John Simon, a pathologist and London's lead medical officer, called Snow's germ theory "peculiar".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Even though Simon understood Snow's theory, he questioned its relation to the cause of cholera.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] On 31 August 1854, after several other outbreaks elsewhere in the city, there was a major outbreak of cholera in Soho.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Over the next three days, 127 people on or near Broad Street died.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] During the next week, three quarters of the residents had fled the area.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] By 10 September, more than 500 people had died and the mortality rate was 12.8 per thousand inhabitants in some parts of the city.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] By the end of the outbreak, 616 people had died.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Many of the victims were taken to the Middlesex Hospital, where their treatment was superintended by Florence Nightingale, who briefly joined the hospital in early September in order to help with the outbreak.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] According to a letter by Elizabeth Gaskell, Nightingale "was up night and day from Friday afternoon (Sept.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] 1) to Sunday afternoon, receiving the poor creatures (chiefly fallen women of that neighbourhood - they had it the worst) who were being constantly brought in - - undressing them - putting on turpentine stupes, et cetera, doing it herself to as many as she could manage".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] By talking to local residents (with the help of Reverend Henry Whitehead), Snow identified the outbreak's source as the public water pump on Broad Street (now Broadwick Street) at Cambridge Street.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Although Snow's chemical and microscope examination of a sample of the water from this Broad Street pump water did not conclusively prove its danger, the patterns of illness and death among residents in Soho persuaded the St James parish authorities to disable the pump by removing its handle.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow later used a dot map to illustrate how cases of cholera occurred around this pump.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] His efforts to connect the incidence of cholera with potential geographic sources was based on what is now known as a Voronoi diagram.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] He mapped the individual water pumps and generated cells representing all the points on his map that were closest to each pump.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The section of Snow's map representing areas in the city where the closest available source of water was the Broad Street pump had the highest incidence of cholera.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] There was one significant anomaly: none of the workers in the nearby Broad Street brewery contracted cholera.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] As they were given a daily allowance of beer, they did not consume water from the nearby well.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] During the brewing process, the wort (un-fermented beer) is boiled in part so that hops can be added.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] This step killed the cholera bacteria in the water they used to brew with, making it safe to drink.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow showed that the Southwark and Vauxhall Waterworks Company was taking water from sewage-polluted sections of the Thames and delivering it to homes, resulting in an increased incidence of cholera among its customers.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow's study is part of the history of public health and health geography.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] It is regarded as the founding event of epidemiology.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] It was discovered later that this public well had been dug 3 feet (0.9 m) from an old cesspit that had begun to leak faecal bacteria.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Waste water from washing nappies used by a baby who had contracted cholera from another source drained into this cesspit.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Its opening was under a nearby house that had been rebuilt further away after a fire and a street widening.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] At the time there were cesspits under most homes.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Most families tried to have their raw sewage collected and dumped in the Thames to prevent their cesspit from filling faster than the sewage could decompose into the soil.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] At the same time, an investigation of cholera transmission was being conducted in Deptford.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Around 90 people died within a few days in that town, where the water was known to be clean, and there had been no previous outbreaks of cholera.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow was informed that the water had recently turned impure.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Before using it, residents had to let it run until the sudsy, sewer-like water turned clear.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow, finding that the water the residents were using was no different from the usual water from their pump, determined that the outbreak must be caused by a leak in the pipes that allowed surrounding sewage and its contaminants to seep in to the water supply.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] This was similar to the Broad Street outbreak.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The incoming water was being contaminated by the increasing levels of sewage, coupled with lack of safe plumbing.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] After the cholera epidemic subsided, government officials replaced the Broad Street pump handle.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] They had responded only to the urgent threat posed to the population, and afterwards they rejected Snow's theory.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] To accept his proposal would have meant indirectly accepting the oral-faecal method of transmission of disease, which was too unpleasant for most of the public to contemplate.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The Broad Street outbreak was an effect rather than a cause of the epidemic.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow's conclusions were not predominantly based on the Broad Street outbreak, as he noted that he hesitated to come to a conclusion based on a population that had predominantly fled the neighbourhood and redistributed itself.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] He feared throwing off results of the study.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] From a mathematical perspective, Snow's innovation was focusing on death rates in areas served by two water companies that drew water from the Thames, rather than basing it on data from victims of the Broad Street pump (which drew water from a well).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow's work also led to a far greater health and safety impact than the removal of the Broad Street pump handle.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Deactivating the pump "hardly made a dent in the citywide cholera epidemic, which went on to claim nearly 3,000 lives".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow was sceptical of the prevailing miasma theory, which held that diseases such as cholera or the Black Death were caused by pollution or a noxious form of "bad air".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The germ theory was not yet established (Louis Pasteur proposed it in 1861).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow did not understand the mechanism by which disease was transmitted, but the evidence led him to believe that it was not foul air.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Based on the pattern of illness among residents, he hypothesized that cholera was spread by an agent in contaminated water.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] He first published his theory in 1849, in an essay titled "On the Mode of Communication of Cholera".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] In 1855 he published a second edition, including a more elaborate investigation of the effect of the water supply in the 1854 Soho outbreak.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The cholera epidemic of 1849–1854 was also related to the water supplied by companies in London at the time.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The main players were the Southwark and Vauxhall Waterworks Company and the Lambeth Waterworks Company.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Both provided water to their customers drawn from the Thames, which was highly contaminated with visible and invisible products and bacteria.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Dr Arthur Hill Hassall examined the filtered water and found it contained animal hair, among other foul substances.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Other companies, such as the New River Company and Chelsea Waterworks Company, were observed to have better filtered water; few deaths occurred in the neighbourhoods they supplied.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] They not only obtained their water from cleaner sources than the Thames, but filtered the water and treated it until there were no obvious contaminants.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] As mentioned above, Snow is known for his influence on public health, which arose after his studies of the cholera epidemic.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] In attempting to figure out who was receiving impure water in each neighbourhood, what is now known as a double-blind experiment fell right into his lap.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow went on to study the water contents from each home through a test performed on each sample.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] In this way, it could be deduced from which supplier the home received its water.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] He concluded that it was indeed impure water from the big companies that allowed cholera to spread rapidly.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] He proved this by observing London prisons, finding that cholera ceased there only a few days after switching to cleaner water sources.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow's analysis of cholera and cholera outbreaks extended past the closure of the Broad Street pump.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] He concluded that cholera was transmitted through and affected the alimentary canal within the human body.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Cholera did not affect either the circulatory or the nervous system and there was no "poison in the blood...in the consecutive fever...the blood became poisoned from urea getting into the circulation".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] According to Snow, this "urea" entered the blood through kidney failure.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Therefore, the fever was caused by kidney failure, not by a poison already present in the subject's bloodstream.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Popular medical practices, such as bloodletting, could not be effective in such a case.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow also argued that cholera was not a product of Miasma.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] "There was nothing in the air to account for the spread of cholera".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] According to Snow, cholera was spread by persons ingesting a substance, not through atmospheric transmittal.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The Reverend Henry Whitehead was an assistant curate at St.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Luke's church in Soho during the 1854 cholera outbreak.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] A former believer in the miasma theory of disease, Whitehead worked to disprove false theories.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] He was influenced by Snow's theory that cholera spreads by consumption of water contaminated by human waste.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow's work, particularly his maps of the Soho area cholera victims, convinced Whitehead that the Broad Street pump was the source of the local infections.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Whitehead joined Snow in tracking the contamination to a faulty cesspool and the outbreak's index case (the baby with cholera).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Whitehead's work with Snow combined demographic study with scientific observation, setting an important precedent for epidemiology.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The London Board of Health, which had recently been given new powers and was presided over by Sir Benjamin Hall, a Cabinet Minister, had several committees, of which the Committee for Scientific Inquiries was placed in charge of investigating the cholera outbreak.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] They were to study the atmospheric environment in London and to examine samples of water from several London water companies.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The committee found that the most contaminated water supply came from the South London water companies, Southwark and Vauxhall.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] As part of the Committee for Scientific Inquiries, Richard Dundas Thomson and Arthur Hill Hassall examined what Thomson called "vibriones".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Thomson examined the occurrence of vibriones in air samples from various cholera wards and Hassall observed vibriones in water samples.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Neither identified vibriones as the cause of cholera.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] As part of its investigation of the cholera epidemic, the Board of Health sent physicians to examine in detail the conditions of the Golden Square neighbourhood and its inhabitants.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The Board of Health ultimately attributed the 1854 epidemic to miasma.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Dr Edwin Lankester was a physician on the local research conglomerate that studied the 1854 Broad Street cholera epidemic.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] In 1866, Lankester wrote about Snow's conclusion that the pump caused the outbreak.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] He agreed with Snow at the time, but his opinion, like Snow's, was not publicly supported.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Lankester subsequently closed the pump due to Snow's theory and data on the pattern of infection, and infection rates dropped significantly.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] He was eventually named the first medical officer of health for St James's parish in London, the area where the pump was.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] A replica pump was installed in 1992 at the site of the 1854 pump.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Every year the John Snow Society holds "Pumphandle Lectures" on public health subjects.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Until 2015, when the pump was removed due to redevelopment, it also held a ceremony there in which it removed and reattached the pump handle to commemorate Snow's discovery.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The pump's original location is marked by a red granite paver, and plaques at the John Snow pub at the corner describe Snow's findings.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The **1896 Summer Olympics**, officially known as the **Games of the I Olympiad**, and commonly known as **Athens 1896** (Greek: Αθήνα 1896), were the first international Olympic Games held in modern history.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Organised by the International Olympic Committee (IOC), which had been created by French aristocrat Pierre de Coubertin, the event was held in Athens, Greece, from 6 to 15 April 1896.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Fourteen nations (according to the IOC, though the number is subject to interpretation) and 241 athletes (all males; this number is also disputed) took part in the games.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Participants were all European or living in Europe, with the exception of the United States team, and over 65% of the competing athletes were Greek.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Winners were given a silver medal, while runners-up received a copper medal.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Retroactively, the IOC has designated the top three finishers in each event as gold, silver, and bronze medalists.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Ten of the 14 participating nations earned medals.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] On April 6, 1896, American James Connolly became the first Olympic medalist in more than 1,500 years, competing in the triple jump.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The United States won the most gold medals, 11, while host nation Greece won the most medals overall, 47.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The highlight for the Greeks was the marathon victory by their compatriot Spyridon Louis.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The most successful competitor was German wrestler and gymnast Carl Schuhmann, who won four events.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Athens had been chosen to stage the inaugural modern Games during a congress organised by Coubertin in Paris on 23 June 1894, during which the IOC was also created.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The main venue was the Panathenaic Stadium, where athletics and wrestling took place; other venues included the Neo Phaliron Velodrome for cycling and the Zappeion for fencing.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony was held in the Panathenaic Stadium on 6 April, during which most of the competing athletes were aligned on the infield, grouped by nation.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] After a speech by the president of the organising committee, Crown Prince Constantine, his father officially opened the Games.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Afterwards, nine bands and 150 choir singers performed an Olympic Hymn, composed by Spyridon Samaras and written by Kostis Palamas.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The 1896 Olympics were regarded as a great success.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Games had the largest international participation of any sporting event to that date.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Panathenaic Stadium overflowed with the largest crowd ever to watch a sporting event.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] After the Games, Coubertin and the IOC were petitioned by several prominent figures, including Greece's King George and some of the American competitors in Athens, to hold all the following Games in Athens.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] However, the 1900 Summer Olympics were already planned for Paris, and, with the exception of the Intercalated Games of 1906, the Olympics did not return to Greece until the 2004 Summer Olympics, 108 years later.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] During the 19th century, several small-scale sports festivals across Europe were named after the ancient Olympic Games.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The 1870 Olympics at the Panathenaic stadium, which had been refurbished for the occasion, had an audience of 30,000 people.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Pierre de Coubertin, a French pedagogue and historian, adopted William Penny Brookes's idea to establish a multi-national and multi-sport event (even though the ancient games only allowed male athletes of Greek origin to participate).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] In 1890, Coubertin wrote an article in *La Revue Athlétique*, which espoused the importance of Much Wenlock, a rural market town in the English county of Shropshire.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] It was here that, in October 1850, the local physician William Penny Brookes founded the Wenlock Olympian Games, a festival of sports and recreations that included athletics and team sports like cricket, football and quoits.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Coubertin also took inspiration from earlier Greek games organised under the name of Olympics by businessman and philanthropist Evangelis Zappas in 1859, 1870 and 1875.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The 1896 Athens Games were funded by the legacies of Zappas and his cousin Konstantinos Zappas and by George Averoff who had been requested by the Greek government to sponsor the second refurbishment of the Panathenaic Stadium.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Greek government did this despite the cost of refurbishing the stadium in marble already being funded in full by Evangelis Zappas forty years earlier.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] On 18 June 1894, Coubertin organised a congress at the Sorbonne, Paris, to present his plans to representatives of sports societies from 11 countries.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Following his proposal's acceptance by the congress, a date for the first modern Olympic Games was discussed; Coubertin suggested that the Games be held concurrently with the 1900 Universal Exposition of Paris.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Concerned that a six-year waiting period might lessen public interest, congress members opted to hold the inaugural Games in 1896.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] With a date established, members of the congress discussed the selection of a host city.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] It is unknown how Athens was chosen: Coubertin and Demetrius Vikelas's descriptions of the selection process contradicted the congress's official minutes.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Most accounts state that several congressmen first proposed London, but Coubertin dissented.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] After a brief discussion with Vikelas, who represented Greece, Coubertin suggested Athens.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Vikelas made the Athens proposal official on 23 June; since Greece had been the original home of the Olympics, the congress unanimously approved the decision.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Vikelas was then elected the first president of the newly established International Olympic Committee (IOC).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The return of the Olympic Games to Greece was well-received by the Greek public, media, and royal family.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Crown Prince conferred their patronage to the games.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] However, the country had financial troubles and was in political turmoil.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The country's prime minister frequently alternated between Charilaos Trikoupis and Theodoros Deligiannis during the last years of the 19th century.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] This instability caused Trikoupis and Stephanos Dragoumis, the president of the Zappas Olympic Committee, which had attempted to organise a series of national Olympiads, to believe that Greece could not host the event.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] In late 1894, the organising committee under Stephanos Skouloudis presented a report that the cost of the Games would be three times higher than originally estimated by Coubertin.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] They concluded the Games could not be held and offered their resignation.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] With the prospect of reviving the Olympic games in doubt, Coubertin and Vikelas commenced a campaign to increase the Olympic movement's popularity.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] On 7 January 1895 Vikelas announced that crown prince Constantine would assume the presidency of the organising committee.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] His first responsibility was to raise the funds necessary to host the Games.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] He relied on the patriotism of the Greek people to motivate them to provide the required finances.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Constantine's enthusiasm increased contributions from the Greek public, raising 330,000 drachmas (equivalent to $1,106,157,688 in 2025).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] A special set of postage stamps was commissioned; the sale of which raised 400,000 drachmas (equivalent to $1,340,797,197 in 2025).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] At the request of Constantine, businessman George Averoff agreed to pay for the restoration of the Panathenaic Stadium.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] As a tribute to his generosity, a statue of Averoff was constructed and unveiled on 5 April 1896 outside the stadium.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The IOC's first regulation, voted on in 1894, was to allow only amateur athletes to participate in the Olympic Games.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The various contests were thus held under amateur regulations, except for fencing matches.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The rules and regulations were not uniform, so the Organising Committee chose among the codes of the various national athletic associations.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The jury, the referees and the game director bore the same names as in antiquity (*Ephor*, *Helanodic* and *Alitarc*).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Prince George acted as final referee; according to Coubertin, "his presence gave weight and authority to the decisions of the ephors".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Women could not compete at the 1896 Summer Olympics because Coubertin felt that their inclusion would be "impractical, uninteresting, unaesthetic and incorrect".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Seven venues were used for the 1896 Summer Olympics.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Panathenaic Stadium was the main venue, hosting four of the nine sports contested.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The town of Marathon hosted the marathon event and the individual road race events.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Fencing was held at the Zappeion, sport shooting at Kallithea, and tennis at the Athens Lawn Tennis Club.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Swimming was held in the Bay of Zea; it was selected because the organizers of the Games wanted to avoid spending money on constructing a special-purpose swimming venue.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Four of the 1896 venues were reused as competition venues for the 2004 Games.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The velodrome would be renovated into a football stadium in the 1960s and was known as Karaiskakis Stadium.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] This venue was renovated in 2003 for use as a football venue for the 2004 Games.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] During the 2004 Games, Panathinaiko Stadium hosted the archery competitions and was the finish line for the athletic marathon event.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The city of Marathon itself served as the starting point for both marathon events during the 2004 Games.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Zappeion served as the first home of the organizing committee (ATHOC) for the 2004 Games from 1998 to 1999, and served as the press center for non-accredited media during those Games.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] On Easter Monday 6 April (25 March according to the Julian calendar used in Greece until 1923) the games of the First Olympiad were officially opened.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Panathenaic Stadium was filled with between 16,000 and 80,000 spectators, including King George I of Greece, his wife Olga, and other members of the royal family.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Most of the competing athletes were aligned on the infield, grouped by nation.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Afterwards, nine bands and 150 choir singers performed an Olympic Hymn, composed by Spyridon Samaras, with words by poet Kostis Palamas.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The first announcements regarding the sporting events to be held featured sports like equestrian and cricket, but these plans were not finalised, and these sports did not make the final program for the Games.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Football is sometimes listed as having been an exhibition or demonstration sport, although whether a football match actually occurred is disputed.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Rowing and sailing events were cancelled on the planned days of competition: sailing due to a lack of special boats in Greece and no foreign entries, and rowing due to poor weather.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The 1896 Summer Olympics programme featured 9 sports encompassing 10 disciplines and 43 events.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The athletics events had the most international field of any of the sports.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The major highlight was the marathon, held for the first time in international competition.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Spyridon Louis, a previously unrecognised water carrier, won the event to become the only Greek athletics champion and a national hero.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Although Greece had been favoured to win the discus and the shot put, the best Greek athletes finished second to American Robert Garrett in both events.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] No world records were set, as few top international competitors had elected to compete and the curves of the track were very tight, making fast times in the running events virtually impossible.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Thomas Burke of the United States won the 100-meter race in 12.0 seconds and the 400-meter race in 54.2 seconds.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Burke was the only one who used the "crouch start" (putting his knee on soil), confusing the jury.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Chile claims one athlete, Luis Subercaseaux, who competed for the nation at the 1896 Summer Olympics.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Subercaseaux's results are not listed in the official report, though that report typically includes only winners and Subercaseaux won no medals.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] He was entered to compete in the 100m, 400m and 800m events but is usually listed as a no show.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] An appraisal of a photo of series 2 of the 100 meters sprint, performed by facial recognition experts of the Chilean forensic police, concluded that Subercaseaux was one of the participants.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The day after the official marathon, Stamata Revithi ran the 40-kilometer course in 5 hours 30 minutes, finishing outside Panathinaiko Stadium.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Some authors, who believe that "Melpomene" and Revithi are the same person, attribute to the latter the more favorable time of 4+1⁄2 hours.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] She was denied entry into the official race as the 1896 Olympics excluded women from competition.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The cycling competitions used the rules of the International Cycling Association.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The newly built Neo Phaliron Velodrome hosted the track cycling events.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Only one road event was held, a race from Athens to Marathon and back (87 kilometres).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] In the track events, the best cyclist was Frenchman Paul Masson, who won the one lap time trial, the sprint event, and the 10,000 meters.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] In the 100 kilometres event, Masson entered as a pacemaker for his compatriot Léon Flameng.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Flameng won the event, after a fall and after stopping to wait for his Greek opponent Georgios Kolettis to fix a mechanical problem.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Austrian fencer Adolf Schmal won the 12-hour race, which was completed by only two cyclists, while the road race event was won by Aristidis Konstantinidis.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The fencing events were held in the Zappeion, which, built with money Evangelis Zappas had given to revive the ancient Olympic Games, had never seen any athletic contests before.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Unlike other sports (in which only amateurs were allowed to take part at the Olympics), professionals were authorised to compete in fencing, though in a separate event.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] These masters professionals were considered gentlemen athletes, just like the amateurs.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Four events were scheduled, but the épée event was cancelled for unknown reasons.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The foil event was won by a Frenchman, Eugène-Henri Gravelotte, who beat his countryman, Henri Callot, in the final.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The other two events were won by Greek fencers: Ioannis Georgiadis won the sabre event, and Leonidas Pyrgos won the masters foil, becoming the first Greek Olympic champion in the modern era.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The gymnastics competition was carried out on the infield of the Panathinaiko Stadium.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Germany sent an 11-man team, which won five of the eight events, including both team events: in the team event on the horizontal bar, the German team was the only entry.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Three Germans added individual titles: Hermann Weingärtner won the horizontal bar event, Alfred Flatow won the parallel bars, and Carl Schuhmann, who also won the wrestling event, won the vault.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Louis Zutter, a Swiss gymnast, won the pommel horse, while Greeks Ioannis Mitropoulos and Nikolaos Andriakopoulos were victorious in the rings and rope climbing events, respectively.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] A regatta of sailing boats was on the program of the Games of the First Olympiad for 31 March 1896 (Julian calendar).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The event was cancelled: the official English report blamed a lack of specialty boats had not been provided while the German version also cited a lack of foreign competitors.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Rowing races were scheduled for the next day, 1 April 1896 (Julian).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Poor weather caused the event to be postponed to 3 pm and German Berthold Küttner stated that he and Adolf Jäger had lined up for the start of the double sculls, the first event to take place.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The event was further postponed to the next day, but the German team still completed the event in the bad weather: they were presented with the winners medal upon the completion of their row.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The next day, the event was formally cancelled when the weather worsened.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee does not recognize Küttner's recollection of the events.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Held at a range at Kallithea, the shooting competition consisted of five events—two using a rifle and three with a pistol.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The first event, the military rifle, was won by Pantelis Karasevdas, the only competitor to hit the target with all of his shots.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The second event, for military pistols, was dominated by two American brothers: John and Sumner Paine.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] They became the first siblings to finish first and second in the same event.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] To avoid embarrassing their hosts, the brothers decided that John would withdraw from the free pistol event.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Sumner Paine won that event, becoming the first relative of an Olympic champion to become Olympic champion himself.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Paine brothers did not compete in the 25-meter pistol event, as the event judges determined that their weapons were not of the required calibre; Ioannis Phrangoudis won the event.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The final event, the free rifle, could not be completed due to darkness and was finalised the next morning, with Georgios Orphanidis winning the competition.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The swimming competition was held in the open sea because the organizers had refused to spend the money necessary for a specially constructed stadium.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Nearly 20,000 spectators lined the Bay of Zea off the Piraeus coast to watch the events.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The water in the bay was cold, and the competitors suffered during their races.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] There were three open events (men's 100-metre freestyle, men's 500-metre freestyle, and men's 1200 metre freestyle), in addition to a special event open only to Greek sailors, all of which were held on the same day (11 April).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] For Alfréd Hajós of Hungary, this meant he could only compete in two of the events, as they were held too close together, which made it impossible for him to adequately recuperate.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Nevertheless, he won the two events in which he swam, the 100 and 1200 meter freestyle.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Hajós later became one of only two Olympians to win a medal in both the athletic and artistic competitions, when he won a silver medal for architecture in 1924.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The 500-meter freestyle was won by Austrian swimmer Paul Neumann, who defeated his opponents by more than a minute and a half.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Although tennis was already a major sport by the end of the 19th century, none of the top players turned up for the tournament in Athens.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The competition was held at the courts of the Athens Lawn Tennis Club, and the infield of the velodrome used for the cycling events.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] John Pius Boland, who won the event, had been entered in the competition by a fellow-student of his at Oxford; the Greek, Konstantinos Manos.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] As a member of the Athens Lawn Tennis sub-committee, Manos had been trying, with the assistance of Boland, to recruit competitors for the Athens Games from among the sporting circles of Oxford University.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] In the first round, Boland defeated Friedrich Traun, a promising tennis player from Hamburg, who had been eliminated in the 100-meter sprint competition.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Boland and Traun decided to team up for the doubles event, in which they reached the final and defeated their Greek opponents after losing the first set.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The sport of weightlifting was still young in 1896, and the rules differed from those in use today.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Competitions were held outdoors, in the infield of the main stadium, and there were no weight limits.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The first event was similar in style to what is now known as the "clean and jerk".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Two competitors stood out: Briton Launceston Elliot and Viggo Jensen of Denmark.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Both of them lifted the same weight, but the jury, with Prince George as the chairman, ruled that Jensen had done so in a better style.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The British delegation, unfamiliar with this tie-breaking rule, lodged a protest.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The lifters were eventually allowed to make further attempts, but neither lifter improved, and Jensen was declared the champion.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Elliot got his revenge in the one hand lift event, which was held immediately after the two-handed one.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Jensen had been slightly injured during his last two-handed attempt and was no match for Elliot, who won the competition easily.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Greek audience was charmed by the British victor, whom they considered very attractive.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] A curious incident occurred during the weightlifting event: a servant was ordered to remove the weights, which appeared to be a difficult task for him.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Prince George came to his assistance; he picked up the weight and threw it a considerable distance with ease, to the delight of the crowd.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] No weight classes existed for the wrestling competition, held in the Panathenaic Stadium, which meant that there would only be one winner among competitors of all sizes.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The rules used were similar to modern Greco-Roman wrestling, although there was no time limit, and not all leg holds were forbidden (in contrast to current rules).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Apart from the two Greek contestants, all the competitors had previously been active in other sports.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Weightlifting champion Launceston Elliot faced gymnastics champion Carl Schuhmann.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The latter won and advanced into the final, where he met Georgios Tsitas, who had previously defeated Stephanos Christopoulos.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Darkness forced the final match to be suspended after 40 minutes; it was continued the following day, when Schuhmann needed only fifteen minutes to finish the bout.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] On the morning of Sunday 12 April (or 31 March, according to the Julian calendar then used in Greece), King George organised a banquet for officials and athletes (even though some competitions had not yet been held).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] During his speech, he made clear that, as far as he was concerned, the Olympics should be held in Athens permanently.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The official closing ceremony was held the following Wednesday after being postponed from Tuesday due to rain.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Again, the royal family attended the ceremony, which was opened by the national anthem of Greece and an ode composed in ancient Greek by George S.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Robertson, a British athlete and scholar.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Afterwards, the king awarded prizes to the winners.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Unlike today, the first-place winners received a silver medal, an olive branch and a diploma, while runners-up received a copper medal, a laurel branch and a diploma.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Third place winners did not receive a prize.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Some winners also received additional prizes.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Spyridon Louis received a cup from Michel Bréal, a friend of Coubertin, who had conceived the marathon event.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Louis then led the medalists on a lap of honour around the stadium, while the Olympic Hymn was played again.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The King then formally announced that the first Olympiad was at an end and left the Stadium, while the band played the Greek national hymn and the crowd cheered.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Like the Greek king, many others supported the idea of holding the next Games in Athens; most of the American competitors signed a letter to the Crown Prince expressing this wish.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Coubertin, however, was heavily opposed to this idea, as he envisioned international rotation as one of the cornerstones of the modern Olympics.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] According to his wish, the next Games were held in Paris, although they would be somewhat overshadowed by the concurrent Universal Exposition.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The concept of national teams was not a major part of the Olympic movement until the Intercalated Games 10 years later, though many sources list the nationality of competitors in 1896 and give medal counts.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] There are significant conflicts with regard to which nations competed.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee gives a figure of 14, but does not list them.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Different sources provide differing lists of nations; some exclude countries like Chile and Bulgaria, but the IOC lists competitors from both countries.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Egypt is also sometimes included due to the participation of Dimitrios Kasdaglis; however, the IOC classifies him as a Greek athlete.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Belgium and Russia had entered the names of competitors, but no athletes from these countries competed.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] National Olympic Committees did not yet exist.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Ten of the fourteen participating nations earned medals, in addition to two medals won by mixed teams (teams made up of athletes from multiple nations).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The IOC has retroactively assigned gold, silver and bronze medals to the three best placed athletes in each event to comport with more recent traditions.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] In this regard, five of the bronze medalists at the Games are unknown: two in swimming and three in gymnastics.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The United States won the most gold medals (11), while host nation Greece won the most medals overall (47), as well as the most silver (18) and bronze (19) medals, finishing with one fewer gold medal than the United States.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The 18th century was a period of rapid growth for London, reflecting an increasing national population, the early stirrings of the Industrial Revolution, and London's role at the centre of the evolving British Empire.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] It saw immigrants and visitors from all over the world, particularly Huguenot migrants from France.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The built-up area of London increased dramatically in this period, particularly westward as areas such as Mayfair and Marylebone were constructed.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Grand aristocratic mansions such as Spencer House were built, as well as churches such as St.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Martin-in-the-Fields and Christ Church Spitalfields.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Crime such as armed robbery and sex work were particularly prevalent, leading to the development of early police forces such as the Bow Street Runners and the Thames River Police.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Capital and corporal punishment such as hanging, penal transportation and the pillory were used, but the period also saw the development of penitentiary prisons such as that at Coldbath Fields.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Londoners saw widespread violence during upheavals such as the Gordon Riots.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Many modern-day cultural institutions come from 18th century London, such as the Royal Society of Arts, the Royal Academy, the British Museum, the Royal Thames Yacht Club, Lord's Cricket Ground, *The Times*, *The Observer,* Theatre Royal Haymarket, and the Royal Opera House.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] London-based artists and writers included Thomas Gainsborough, William Hogarth, Jonathan Swift, Mary Wollstonecraft, and Samuel Johnson.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] London's economy was massively boosted by its shipping industry, but other important industries included silkweaving.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Many modern-day businesses trace their origins back to 18th-century London, including Sotheby's, WHSmith, and Schweppes.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In order to transport goods and people, many new turnpikes and canals were constructed, and educational movements aimed at working-class children, such as Sunday schools, were pioneered in this period.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] At the beginning of the period, about 500,000 people lived in London.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] By 1713, this number had risen to 630,000; by 1760, it was 740,000, and by the end of the century, it was just over 1 million.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The average height of a male Londoner was 5 ft 7+1⁄4 in (171 cm) and the average height of a female Londoner was 5 ft 1+3⁄4 in (157 cm).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In 1768, the abolitionist Granville Sharp estimated that there were 20,000 Black people in domestic service in London.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] This included some who were enslaved, as evidenced by "for sale" or "runaway" notices in London newspapers.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In the aftermath of the American Revolutionary War in the 1780s, there was a small influx of Black Americans who had fought for the British and were therefore no longer welcome in the United States, many of whom become homeless.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Some Black Londoners became well known through their writings, such as Ignatius Sancho, Olaudah Equiano, Ottobah Cugoano, Robert Wedderburn, Ukawsaw Gronniosaw, Ayuba Suleiman Diallo, and Phillis Wheatley.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Other famous Black Londoners of the day include the violinist George Bridgetower, the fencing master Julius Soubise, and the aristocrats Dido Belle and William Ansah Sessarakoo.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Around the docks in the East End was a population of sailors from India and east Asia known as "lascars" employed on ships belonging to the East India Company.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The company ran a boarding house for them called Orchard House in Blackwall.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In the wealthier West End of London, Indians were more likely to be employed as domestic servants by officers and former officers of the East India Company.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In 1765, the *munshi* Mirza Sheikh I'tesamuddin became the first-known educated Indian to visit London.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] He wrote a book in Persian on his experiences in Europe which was later translated into English by James Edward Alexander.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] London had populations of immigrants from various European countries.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] After the rights of French Protestants called Huguenots were repealed in 1688, thousands fled to London.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] At the beginning of the period, there were an estimated 25,000 Huguenots in London, particularly in Soho and Spitalfields.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] At their height, there were 23 French churches in London.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Successful Huguenots included the sculptor Louis François Roubiliac and the optician John Dollond.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] There was also a community of French Catholic immigrants, who ran French-language newspapers such as the *Courier Politique et Littéraire* and the *Courier de Londres*.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Well-known Londoners from other European countries include the painters Godfrey Kneller, and Johan Zoffany; and the sculptors Peter Scheemakers, Michael Rysbrack and Giuseppe Ceracchi.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In 1750, a population of the Bohemian Protestant sect called Moravians settled on Cheyne Walk in Chelsea.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] They established a Moravian church and burial ground.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] An estimated 30,000 Irish immigrants lived in London by the end of the period.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Some were particularly successful, including Robert Barker, Hans Sloane, James Barry, Charles Macklin, Jonathan Swift, Laurence Sterne, Oliver Goldsmith, and Richard Brinsley Sheridan.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Theoretically, Romani people and travellers had been expelled from England since the 1560s, but there was nonetheless a community in London in the 18th century, particularly in Norwood.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] They were particularly associated with horse dealing and fortune-telling at London's fairs.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Well-known travellers of the period included Jacob Rewbrey of Westminster, Margaret Finch of Norwood, and Diana Boswell from Dulwich.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Historian Jerry White estimates that there were about 750 Jewish people living in London at the beginning of the period.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] By the end of the century, that number had risen to about 15,000.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In 1701, Bevis Marks synagogue opened to cater to Sephardic Jews descended from Spanish and Portuguese immigrants.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] It is still a working synagogue to this day.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Ashkenazi Jews, descended from Dutch, German and central European immigrants, used the Great Synagogue in Duke's Place, the Hambro' Synagogue off Fenchurch Street, and the New Synagogue on Leadenhall Street.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Practising Jews could not join the city's trade guilds, and so many Jewish business owners lived outside the city, in places like Aldgate and Whitechapel.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Michael Leoni was a famous Jewish singer, and Daniel Mendoza a famous Jewish boxer.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] There were smaller numbers of people who came from further afield, such as Mehemet von Königstreu and Ernst August Mustapha, Turkish valets to George I.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] London also drew in people from all over the globe, even if they only visited for a short time.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Examples include the Native American chief Tomochichi and his retinue, who met George II in 1734; the Raiatean man Mai, who visited in 1774 and had his portrait painted by the artist Joshua Reynolds; and the Aboriginal Australians Bennelong and Yemmerrawanne, who visited in 1793.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] A map of London made in 1700 (in black and white) compared to a map made in 1763 (in colour).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] London has spread much further west in the second map, as far as Park Lane (marked as Tyburn Lane).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] London's growth in the 18th century was marked above all by the westward shift of the population away from the City of London.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Westminster was intensively developed, with new districts like Mayfair housing Britain's wealthiest aristocratic families.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Cavendish Square and Hanover Square were both laid out in the 1710s, while the Portman Estate, which occupies the western half of Marylebone, began its own building program in the 1750s with the granting of commercial leases, followed by the commencement of building on Portman Square in 1764.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Comparison of London maps made in the mid-17th century with ones made in the mid-18th century also reveal that the new developments were much more likely to be built along grid structures.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The most exclusive area, Mayfair, was intensively built up with luxury townhouses on an area occupied by seven different estates: the Grosvenor, Burlington, Berkeley, Curzon, Milfield, Conduit Mead, and Albemarle Ground estates.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The Grosvenor estate, in the northwest corner between Oxford Street and Park Lane, was the most substantial private plot of land, featuring an orderly grid network of streets constructed around Grosvenor Square in the early 1720s.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] By 1738 "nearly the whole space between Piccadilly and Oxford Street was covered with buildings as far as Tyburn Lane [Park Lane], except in the south-western corner about Berkeley Square and Mayfair".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Further west, the Cadogan Estate began working on the area between Knightsbridge and Sloane Square in 1777.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] To the south, the area now known as Elephant & Castle was also laid out in this period, with a road from Westminster Bridge connecting up to Borough High Street, and the New Kent Road also constructed.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] To the north, new developments sprang up around between Paddington and Islington such as Pentonville, named after its landlord, Henry Penton; and Somers Town, named after its landlord, Charles Cocks, 1st Baron Somers.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Construction began on Bedford Square in 1775, which has been called "the most perfect of the London squares of the period", and Finsbury Square was begun in 1777.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Building started on Camden Town in 1791, named after the 1st Earl Camden.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Rural villages surrounding Westminster and the city also grew in population and were gradually incorporated into the metropolis: areas like Bethnal Green and Shadwell to the east, or Paddington and St.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In 1750 the London topographer John Noorthouck reckoned that London proper consisted of 46 former villages, two cities (Westminster and the City of London proper), and one borough (Southwark).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Buckingham House, later known as Buckingham Palace, was bought by George III in 1762.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In 1783, work began on expanding and renovating Carlton House for the then Prince of Wales, which took years to be completed as well as huge amounts of taxpayer money, only for the Prince to live there for a very short amount of time.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] 10 Downing Street was acquired by the Crown and offered to the Prime Minister Robert Walpole.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] As he already had many houses and didn't want to pay to upkeep another, he accepted it as a perk of his position, beginning the tradition of passing the house down to each successive Prime Minister.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] It was substantially remodelled by the architect William Kent.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The residence of the Lord Mayor of the City of London, Mansion House, was completed in 1753 after having been designed by architect George Dance the Elder.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The current Treasury building was completed in 1736.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Bevis Marks Synagogue was one of the first new religious buildings of the period, opening in 1701.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In 1710, the final stone was added to St.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Paul's Cathedral, designed by Christopher Wren.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Paul's, which had been completely destroyed in the Great Fire of London.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] A flurry of church-building between 1711 and 1730 also saw the construction of Christ Church Spitalfields, St.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] John's Smith Square, and Grosvenor Chapel.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] After this, further churches built in the period include St.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] George the Martyr, Southwark (1736), St.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Another burst of church-building occurred towards the end of the period, with new churches such as St.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The period also saw the construction of several bridges across the Thames alongside London Bridge.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] With the completion of Westminster Bridge in 1750, London gained a much needed second crossing onto the south bank, and Blackfriars Bridge opened in 1769.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] To the west, Putney Bridge was built in 1729, Kew built its first bridge in 1759, and Richmond Bridge opened in 1777.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The first Freemasons' Hall was built on Great Queen Street in 1776.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Severndroog Castle was built in 1784 to commemorate the seagoing victories of Sir William James, who had died the previous year.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Trinity House was built for the body that governs English and Welsh lighthouses in 1795.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Shop fronts also began to be built with large windows for passers-by to see the goods inside, examples of which can still be seen at 88 Dean Street and James Lock & Co on St.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] New government offices included Somerset House, the Admiralty, and Horse Guards.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] To accommodate the rapid growth of population, Parliament enacted building legislation and initiated important infrastructure projects.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The Fleet River, which was so filled with rubbish and sewage that it had been a health hazard for many years, was finally covered over in 1733.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The New Road running between Paddington and Islington was constructed beginning in 1756.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Intended as a drover's road upon which livestock could be driven to Smithfield Market without encountering the congested road network of the city further south, the 60 ft (18 m) wide New Road was London's first bypass and served as the informal northern boundary for London for years to come.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The City Road was added in 1761, connecting the Angel to Finsbury Square.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] To improve traffic, the houses on London Bridge were removed in 1757, the Holbein Gate in Whitehall was removed in 1759, and the gates of the city were removed 1760–1777.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] A London building from the 17th century (in black and white) compared to one built in the 18th century (in colour).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Notice how the later building has no overhanging storeys or signs, and the window frames are recessed slightly.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] From 1707, buildings in London were no longer permitted with upper storeys overhanging the lower ones, so facades on future buildings were strictly vertical.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] After the Building Regulation Act 1709 (7 Ann. c.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] 17), wooden window frames were required to be recessed at least 4 inches into the wall to prevent the spread of fire up a building's facade.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In 1762, shop signs that hung down were banned in the City and Westminster, and had to be fixed flat to the building instead to prevent them blocking out sunlight and falling on people walking underneath.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The Building Act 1777 set building requirements for new housing and sought to eliminate rampant jerry-building and shoddy construction work.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Housing was divided into four "rates" based on ground rents, with each of the rates accorded their own strict building codes.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The Building Act accounts for the remarkable uniformity of Georgian terraced housing and squares in London built in subsequent decades, which critics like John Summerson criticized for their "inexpressible monotony".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Landmark legislation included the Westminster Paving Act 1765 (5 Geo.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] 50), which required streets be equipped with pavements, drainage, and lighting.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The success of the legislation inspired the London Paving and Lighting Act 1766 (6 Geo.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] 26), which extended the same provisions across the whole city and required that houses be numbered and streets and pavements be cleansed and swept regularly.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Street lighting was more extensive than in any other city in Europe, something which amazed foreign visitors to the capital in the late 18th century.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The practice of numbering houses also dates from this period, with some sources claiming it started in New Burlington Street.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The practice of putting street names on signs at each corner was taken up by the city from 1765 onwards.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Armed robbery was particularly common in London, either by highwaymen (on horseback) or footpads (on foot).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] One gang, run by a man called Obadiah Lemon, used fishing hooks to steal hats and wigs through open coach windows, or leapt on top and cut through the roof.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] George III himself was robbed of his shoe buckles and spare change while walking in Kensington Gardens.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] During the 1750s, several outyling towns in London's suburbs organised their own guard patrols to combat robbers on their roads.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] For example, Blackheath residents offered rewards for information on highwaymen in 1753, and Kentish Town inhabitants paid to hire guards in 1756.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Pickpocketing was also particularly common in London, where large crowds often gathered at executions and theatre performances.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] There was also large amounts of theft on the river, as ships laden with valuable goods waited with skeleton crews for a berth in the Pool of London. £70,000 worth of sugar alone was stolen per year from boats on the river.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Sex work was another common crime, particularly associated with Covent Garden.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In 1758, it was estimated that 3,000 sex workers lived in London.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] On one routine sweep, constables arrested 22 sex workers in Covent Garden, two of whom were men dressed as women.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In 1757, a catalogue of London's sex workers was published called *Harris's List of Covent Garden Ladies*, which detailed the names, locations, and descriptions of hundreds of workers in the capital.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Although the crime of buggery was punishable by death, London had several establishments known as "molly houses", where queer men could meet.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] According to one homophobic pamphlet of the time, men in molly houses took on female personas and performed mock weddings and birth ceremonies.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The 18th century saw a huge backlash against molly houses, with the publication of pamphlets such as *The Sodomites' Shame and Doom*, and groups such as the Society for the Reformation of Manners attempting to track down queer men and have them prosecuted.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] One of the most famous molly houses was Mother Clap's in Holborn, which was raided in 1726, resulting in 40 arrests and three hangings.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Mother Clap herself was sentenced to the pillory and two years in prison.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] There was no organised police force in this period.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In times of serious emergency, or in the case of organised gangs, the authorities could deploy the military, but this was deeply unpopular, both with citizens and with the military themselves.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] There were small, specialised forces, such as the King's Messengers (who dealt with sedition, particularly Jacobites), the Press Messengers (who dealt with seditious publishers) and the City Marshals (localised to the City of London).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Local magistrates, or Justices of the Peace, could issue warrants for criminals; and their officers, constables, would apprehend them.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Constables were also responsible for policing low-level criminals such as sex workers and fortune tellers, detecting crime, and raising the "hue and cry".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Below them, beadles were responsible for making sure that those who qualified for "outdoor relief" were receiving it, acting as town crier, and supervising the town watch; and the watch patrolled the streets at night armed with a lantern and a cudgel to discourage crime.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Corruption was endemic, meaning that if one wanted someone prosecuted, one had to do all the leg-work oneself, bribing officers at every stage.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In previous eras, Londoners had been able to claim sanctuary at monasteries and former monasteries in order to avoid the law, but by 1712 this practice had been eradicated.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Bow Street Magistrates' Court opened in 1740 in Covent Garden.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] One of the magistrates, Henry Fielding, established the Bow Street Runners in 1749 as an early form of a police force.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] They took the form of six parish constables who acted as bounty hunters, being paid a regular salary plus bonuses for any criminal they apprehended who was successfully prosecuted.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The Bow Street Runners were unusual in that they are generally agreed to have not been corrupt.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In 1754, John Fielding took over as chief magistrate, and his writings on the model popularised the concept across the country as he advocated for a national police force.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Fielding is even credited with popularising the word "police".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] By the end of the century, there were eight or nine other such groups belonging to magistrates' courts around London.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Inspired by the Bow Street Runners, in 1798 Patrick Colquhoun set up the River Police, sometimes called the first professional police force in the country, which tackled crime in the docks and Pool of London.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Throughout the period, the number of crimes, especially property crimes, subject to the death penalty ballooned under a period of English law known as the Bloody Code.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Of those executions, London played host to the vast majority.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Hanging was a common punishment for several crimes.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In the period 1750–1775, 3.85 people per 100,000 were hanged per year on average, and only 12% of these were for murder, as the number of people executed for property crimes grew under the Bloody Code.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Hangings were public, and could attract large crowds depending on the fame of the victims.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] When the thief Jack Sheppard, who had escaped from prison multiple times, was finally hanged at Tyburn in 200,000 people reportedly came to see it.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In the 1780s, the authorities stopped use of Tyburn as London's main execution site in favour of Newgate Prison.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The last person executed at Tyburn was a man called John Austin in 1782.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] London employed a chief hangman and an assistant for this job, at a salary of £50 per year plus a guinea per execution.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The most famous of these was John Price, who was himself hanged for murder in 1718.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] As an extra punishment for particularly cold-blooded crimes, a hanged body would be publicly displayed in chains, such as a Mrs Phipoe in 1797, whose body was displayed at the Old Bailey.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Pirates were generally hanged at Execution Dock on the foreshore of the Thames near Brewhouse Lane and Wapping High Street, and the bodies would be left there until they had been covered by three tides of the river.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] This was done to Captain William Kidd in 1701.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Burning at the stake was used as a punishment for women who committed treason, as in the case of Katherine Hayes, who was burned in 1726 at Tyburn for murdering her husband.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] As the period went on, this sentence changed to include being hanged before the body was burned at the stake.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Men who committed treason were sentenced to be hanged, drawn and quartered, as was the case for several soldiers who supported the 1745 Jacobite Rebellion, who were executed on Kennington Common.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Nobles who committed treason were permitted to die by beheading.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The last person to be executed by beheading in Britain was Lord Lovat on Tower Hill in 1747.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Prisoners who refused to plead either guilty or not guilty would be "pressed" to death, otherwise known as *peine forte et dure,* by being slowly crushed by large stones, a practice abolished in 1772.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] After the Transportation Act 1717, transportation became another common punishment.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] At the beginning of the period, convicts were transported to the American colonies, where their labour would be sold to a plantation for the duration of their sentence, but after the American Revolutionary War, the authorities looked for a new location.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] London's first shipment of convicts to Australia set off in 1787, and landed in Port Jackson, in modern-day Sydney.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Some crimes were punished by whipping, which could take place either in public, tied to the back of a cart and being marched through the streets; or in the private confines of a prison.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Another punishment designed to inflict public humiliation was the pillory.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] As the century went on, those sentenced to the pillory would increasingly find themselves at the mercy of the mob, who could either protect them while they served their sentence or throw rotten vegetables, manure, dead animals, or rocks.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Several people were killed by mobs while in the pillory.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In 1779, a new kind of prison was introduced called the pentitentiary, with an emphasis on forcing criminals to do hard labour.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] London's prisons were often filthy and its officers corrupt.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In 1726, an investigation into conditions in the Fleet Prison revealed that families had to bribe the warden to hand over the bodies of their family members who had died inside; and that one man called Jacob Solas had been chained up next to a sewer and a rubbish heap for two months.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In 1750, an outbreak of "jail fever" at the Old Bailey next to Newgate Prison killed at least 50 people.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In 1715, claimant to the throne James Stuart landed in Scotland in what is known as the Jacobite Rebellion.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In London, his supporters rioted, burning a portrait of William III, drinking toasts to James II, and attacking those who refused to join them.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Soldiers were mobilised in Hyde Park in the event that Stuart should reach the capital.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In 1745, Stuart made another attempt, leading to a military camp being set up at Finchley in case the Jacobite forces reached London from Scotland.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In the end, they only made it as far as Derby.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In 1763, the politician John Wilkes came under scrutiny after he wrote articles criticising George III.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] He was briefly imprisoned in the Tower of London, and his newspaper, the North Briton, was burned in a ritual execution outside the Royal Exchange.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] During the burning, Londoners rushed to rescue copies from the flames, and attacked the sheriff in his coach.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Later that year, the MP Samuel Martin challenged Wilkes to a duel in Hyde Park, during which he shot Wilkes in the stomach.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] When Wilkes won an election in 1768, his supporters marched through the streets from Brentford to London, and when they got there, they broke all the windows in the newly built Mansion House.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] On 10 May, a soldiers fired upon a group of Wilkes' supporters at St.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] George's Fields, and several people were killed.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The following year, Wilkes won a re-election, but the government nonetheless announced his opponent as the winner.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] When supporters of the government marched to St.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] James's, they were pelted with mud by Wilkes' supporters.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Wilkes was so popular among Londoners that in 1774 there was a crush to be one of the people who got to pull his coach, and one man was killed.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] During the American Revolutionary War, the City of London generally favoured the colonists, arguing that their taxation was too heavy and that the government should not use violence against them.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In 1775, the City sent a petition to the king with 1,171 signatures to this effect.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In 1780, London was rocked by the Gordon Riots, an uprising led by Lord George Gordon against Roman Catholic emancipation.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Severe damage was caused to Catholic churches and homes, and rioters also attacked legal buildings such as the Bow Street magistrates' court, Newgate Prison, the King's Bench Prison, the Fleet Prison, and The Clink.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Houses of Protestants who were sympathetic to Catholics, such as those of George Savile, Lord Justice Cox, and the Earl of Mansfield, were also destroyed.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] One newspaper at the time estimated that over 450 people were killed in the riots themselves, and 35 were executed in the aftermath, although George Gordon himself escaped the gallows.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The Royal Society of Arts was founded in 1754 in Crane Court.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In 1774, they moved into their current address on John Adam Street.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The Royal Academy was established in 1768 at Somerset House as an art school that ran a regular exhibition of artworks by its members.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Its first president was the painter Joshua Reynolds, and its pupils included J.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Popular London portrait artists included Arthur Devis, John Wootton, Allan Ramsay, Johann Zoffany, Thomas Gainsborough, and Joshua Reynolds.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] William Hogarth created satirical paintings such as *A Rake's Progress* that became famous as engraved prints.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] James Barry created early Romantic paintings.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Only eight visitors saw it on its first day of operation.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The Mozart family arrived in London in 1764, staying at Cecil Court, Ebury Street and Frith Street, and performing in several concerts.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] During this time, Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart wrote several works including his first symphony, Symphony No.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The pianoforte also appeared in London for the first time in this period, with a concert including the instrument being performed in 1767 at the Covent Garden Theatre, now known as the Royal Opera House.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] James's gentlemen's clubs date from this period, including Almack's, Brooks's, and Boodle's.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] These clubs offered society and gambling to wealthy gentlemen, and many are still in operation today.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] James's, other important gentlemen's clubs were founded such as the Kit-Cat Club, which met around the Strand and included famous Whigs of the day.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Bare-knuckle boxing, also known as prizefighting, was incredibly popular, despite being illegal.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Famous boxers included James Figg, Jack Broughton, Tom Johnson, and Daniel Mendoza.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Broughton introduced an early form of boxing gloves called "mufflers" and laid down a set of rules for his boxing arena on Tottenham Court Road in order to ensure the safety of participants.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] These rules have been called the "first written rules to be applied to any sport".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In 1749, London held Britain's first-known open yacht race, from Greenwich to the mouth of the Thames.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In 1775, the Cumberland Fleet became the first yacht club to organise races.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In the 1750s, the Jockey Club was formed by aristocratic regulars at the Star and Garter Club in Pall Mall.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The first attempt at codifying the rules of cricket was made by the London Cricket Club at the Artillery Ground in Finsbury in 1744.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Lord's cricket ground was founded in this period, with the wine merchant Thomas Lord leasing out a parcel of land in Islington for his friends to play cricket on in 1787.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The Marylebone Cricket Club grew out of players at this venue, with the club's earliest minute books also dating back to this year.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] One of the most popular places to go for entertainment in London was Vauxhall Gardens, which reopened with new management in 1732 as the "New Spring Gardens".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] 18th-century Londoners could also visit assembly rooms such as the Pantheon on Oxford Street, where people could enjoy Vauxhall Garden-style activities such as dances and masquerades in all weathers.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Bull baiting and bear baiting were popular pastimes, with more exotic animals being brought in occasionally.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] For example, in 1747, a former boxer called John Broughton advertised a tiger baiting on Oxford Street.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Areas around London also held annual fairs, such as Bartholomew Fair and Southwark Fair, which was abolished in 1762.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] One attraction of Southwark Fair was the acrobat Mr Cadman, who walked across a rope tied from building to building over the street.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Occasionally, the winter was cold enough to make the Thames freeze completely, allowing for "frost fairs" on the ice, such as in 1789, when a bearbaiting took place on the ice, and an ox was roasted whole at Shadwell.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Towards the end of the period, hot air balloon flights became a regular feature of London's entertainment offering, with the first balloon launch in England taking place in 1783 at the Artillery Ground near Finsbury Square.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] This first attempt was unmanned; the first manned balloon flight in the country was undertaken the following year from the same place by Vincenzo Lunardi.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The Irish artist Robert Barker began this trend, and in fact coined the term *panorama,* in the 1790s.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] London played host to many important writers of the 18th century such as Jonathan Swift, Alexander Pope, Henry Fielding, Edmund Burke, Oliver Goldsmith, Fanny Burney, and Daniel Defoe.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Londoners such as Mary Astell and Mary Wollstonecraft wrote early feminist works, and poets such as Stephen Duck wrote about the working-class.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Britain's first daily newspaper, the *Daily Courant*, was sold 1702–1735 from Ludgate Hill.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] *Gentleman's Magazine* began publication in 1731 and continued until 1907.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The first English Sunday newspaper, the *British Gazette and Sunday Monitor*, began publication in 1780.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] *The Times* was founded in 1785 as the *Daily Universal Register*, and *The Observer* in 1791.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In 1755, Samuel Johnson published one of the first dictionaries of the English language, which had taken him eight years to write from his house in Gough Square.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Johnson's dictionary attempted to be more comprehensive than previous attempts, and included quotations showing where each word had come from.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] What is now the Theatre Royal Haymarket opened in 1705 as the Queen's Theatre.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The Royal Opera House first opened in 1732 as the Covent Garden Theatre.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] 1728 saw the opening of *The Beggar's Opera* at Lincoln's Inn Fields.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Unlike the Italian-style operas that London audiences were used to, this used well-known folk songs and hymns from the time with the lyrics changed, so that audiences could sing along.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] It ran for 60 performances, considered a very long run at the time.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] One particularly famous star of the stage in the period was David Garrick, who had his debut in 1741 at Goodman's Fields Theatre.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The famous actress Sarah Siddons first appeared at the Drury Lane Theatre in 1775, playing Portia in *The Merchant of Venice.* This period also saw the rise of famous playwrights such as Richard Brinsley Sheridan, whose play *The Rivals* opened at Covent Garden in the same year.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] After the 1737 Licensing Act, all plays where the audience were charged for tickets had to be licensed by the Lord Chamberlain, a national censorship that lasted until 1968.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Pantomime has its origins in 18th-century London theatre, with *The Tavern Bilkers* at the Theatre Royal Drury Lane in 1702 being a possible candidate for the world's first pantomime.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In 1720, Lady Mary Wortley Montagu returned to London from travels in the Ottoman Empire, where she acquired knowledge of smallpox inoculation.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In 1721, she had her three-year-daughter publicly inoculated by the surgeon Charles Maitland at the Royal College of Physicians.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] This resulted in a short-lived wave of popularity for inoculation among the wealthy in London, including the Princess of Wales.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Many new people were training to become surgeons, and needed corpses to practice on and learn from.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] From 1752, the bodies of six hanged criminals were given to the Royal College of Surgeons for this purpose each year, but this was nowhere near the number required.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In 1767, Dr William Hunter opened a School of Anatomy in Great Windmill Street to showcase dissections for medical students.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] This need created demand for a class of criminal known as bodysnatchers, who stole recently deceased bodies from graveyards.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In response, some churches built watchhouses and hired guards.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Excessive drinking was a common hazard to Londoners' health, particularly during the Gin Craze in the first half of the century.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In 1720, London's distilleries produced 2.5 million gallons of spirits per year.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Newspapers such as the *London Journal* attributed several deaths to gin-drinking, such as that of a porter in Holborn who "drank so plentifully of Geneva, with his wife, that he died upon the spot [...] 'tis said that they drank three pints apiece, in a little more than an hour".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] A Whitechapel stationer and rag merchant, William Addis, is credited with inventing the toothbrush in 1780.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] At the beginning of the period, London had two main hospitals: St.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Beginning in the 1720s, there was a movement to build new hospitals using charitable donations, which were called "voluntary" hospitals.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Donors could nominate patients to receive free treatment.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In 1720, Westminster Hospital was opened in Petty France.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] 1725 saw the opening of Guy's Hospital, which was originally intended for up to 400 poor patients with incurable conditions, which other hospitals such as St.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] George's Hospital was founded in 1733, and the London Hospital in 1740.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In 1739, Britain's first midwifery school was opened at St.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Middlesex Hospital opened in 1745 on Windmill Street with just 18 beds.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The London Hospital moved to large new buildings on Whitechapel Road in the 1750s, where they still are to this day.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] From the 1750s, there was a wave of new maternity or "lying-in" hospitals, beginning with the British Lying-In Hospital in 1749, and further examples being built in 1750, 1752, and 1765.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] London had a smallpox hospital at Coldbath Fields from the 1740s, which moved to St.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] London's main lunatic asylum, the Bethlehem Royal Hospital (better known as Bedlam) long predates this period, but in 1770 it banned the longstanding practice of allowing tourists to pay to view its inmates.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The hospital still operates in London to this day.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] England's first veterinary college was also founded in this period- the Royal Veterinary College, originally based in Camden in 1791.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Another way people could get medical help in this period was through dispensaries.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] A dispensary was an organisation that provided medical help using money donated by wealthy people.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] These donors could then write letters of recommendation to allow poorer people to access treatment.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The first free dispensary in London was founded in Red Lion Square in 1769.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] King's Cross had several springs which were thought to have medicinal qualities.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In 1759, the Bagnigge Wells opened, with a pump room where visitors could drink the water, play skittles, and hear concerts.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Water could be bought for 3d per gallon.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In 1770, a spa was also founded in Bermondsey, near what is now known as Spa Road.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In September 1720, stock in the South Sea Company collapsed.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Many wealthy Londoners lost large amounts of money (the Duke of Chandos lost £700,000), and in January 1721, one newspaper suggested that data on the number of suicides caused by the crash should be collected.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The 18th century saw the rise and fall of London's silk trade, run in chief by Protestant Huguenot families fleeing persecution in Catholic France and setting up silk looms in Spitalfields.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In the 1710s, calico fabric imported from India began to undercut London silk, and in 1719, 4,000 Spitalfields silkweavers rioted in an anti-calico demonstration, throwing ink and acid at women wearing calico fabric.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Throughout the century, silk weavers continued to protest and riot against the intrusion of cheaper fabrics into their market, and against poor treatment by weaving masters.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In 1763, a group of silkweavers broke into their master's house, broke his looms, cut up his bolts of silk, and burned the master in effigy.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In the aftermath of one silkweavers' riot in 1769, two leaders were hanged at Newgate Prison.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Silkweavers also celebrated victories, such as the law passed in 1766 banning French silk from being imported.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Silkweavers processed through the streets playing "God Save The King", and lit bonfires and fireworks.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] A huge portion of London's economy was built through trade, particularly shipping.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In 1790, 70% of Britain's imports and 56% of its exports came through the capital.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Ships coming to London were required to dock at the legal quays in the "Pool of London", a complex of many tiny quays and wharves along the side of the Thames from London Bridge to the Tower.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] This was extremely congested, and so throughout the period, more docks were added elsewhere along the river, such as Greenland Dock in Rotherhithe and the East India Company's dock at Blackwall.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Some London companies and individuals profited through colonial exploits around the world, notably in the Caribbean and India.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] For example, twice-Lord Mayor William Beckford was from a family of Jamaican plantation owners, at the time of his death owned 3,000 people across 13 plantations, and was supposedly the first English commoner to be a millionnaire upon his death.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The East India Company was based at Leadenhall Street, and alone accounted for 19% of British imports by value in the last quarter of the century.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The London Stock Exchange was founded in 1773 in Threadneedle Street.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The 18th century in Britain is often referred to as being subject to "turnpike mania", wherein many roads were placed in the custody of private trusts, who set up tollbooths along the road to pay for its upkeep.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] London's first turnpikes were set up in 1711: along Edgware Road from Kilburn to Hertfordshire, and the road from Highgate to Barnet.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] By 1720, there were five more: between Shoreditch and Enfield; Tyburn and Uxbridge; Kensington and Staines and Colnbrook; Southwark to Greenwich and Lewisham; and Westminster to New Cross.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Towards the end of the period, canals began to be constructed across London to allow for the movement of goods.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The Limehouse Cut was opened in 1770 to allow boats from Hertfordshire to reach London's docks without having to go round the Isle of Dogs.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] As bridges across the Thames were few and congested, many Londoners crossed the river on taxi-boats operated by watermen.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] These watermen sometimes held rowing races, and in 1715, a comic actor called Thomas Doggett offered a cash prize and a new coat and badge to the winner of a race between newly qualified watermen.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] This race, called Doggett's Coat and Badge, is still held annually in London to this day.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] The Society for Promoting Christian Knowledge was founded just before the beginning of this period in 1699, and ran charity schools throughout the century to provide education to London's poorest children.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] By the end of the century, there were 179 such schools in the city.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In 1758, the Orphan Working School was founded in Hoxton to teach children job skills such as shoemaking, as well as literacy and religion.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] In 1782, the Surrey Chapel opened on Blackfriars Road with 13 Sunday schools, which provided education for 3,000 children.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] 18th-century London saw England's first school for deaf and mute children, founded in 1792 in Bermondsey.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/18th-century-london] Several long-running adult education institutions were also founded in this period, such as the Linnean Society and the Royal Institution.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The **1900 Summer Olympics** (French: *Jeux olympiques d'été de 1900*), today officially known as the **Games of the II Olympiad** (*Jeux de la IIe olympiade*) and also known as **Paris 1900**, were an international multi-sport event that took place in Paris, France, from 14 May to 28 October 1900.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] No opening or closing ceremonies were held.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] At the Olympic Congress of 1894, which convened in the Sorbonne building, Pierre de Coubertin proposed that the Olympic Games should take place in Paris in 1900.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] However, the delegates to the conference were unwilling to wait six years and lobbied to hold the first games in 1896.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A decision was made to hold the first Olympic Games in 1896 in Athens and have Paris host the second Games.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Games were held as part of the 1900 Exposition Universelle (World's Fair).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In total, 1,226 competitors took part in 19 different sports.[note1] This number relies on certain assumptions about which events were and were not "Olympic".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Many athletes, some of whom had won events, were unaware they had competed in the Olympic Games.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Women took part in the games for the first time, with sailor Hélène de Pourtalès, born Helen Barbey in New York City, becoming the first female Olympic champion.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The decision to hold competitions on a Sunday brought protests from many American athletes, who traveled as representatives of their colleges and were expected to withdraw rather than compete on their religious day of rest.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Most of the winners in 1900 did not receive medals but were given cups or trophies.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Professionals competed in fencing, as was tradition, and Albert Robert Ayat (France), who won the épée for amateurs and masters, was awarded a prize of 3,000 F (equivalent to €13,896 in 2025).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Some events were contested for the only time in the history of the Games, including angling, motor racing, ballooning, cricket, croquet, Basque pelota, 200m swimming obstacle race and underwater swimming.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] This was also the only Olympic Games in history to use live animals (pigeons) as targets during the shooting event.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The host nation of France fielded 72% of all athletes (720 of the 997) and won the most gold, silver and bronze medal placings.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] U.S. athletes won the second-most in each while fielding the fifth-most participants, 75.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] British athletes won the third-most in each while fielding the second most participants, 102.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 Games were held as part of the 1900 Exposition Universelle.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Baron de Coubertin believed this would help public awareness of the Olympics and submitted elaborate plans to rebuild the ancient site of Olympia, complete with statues, temples, stadia, and gymnasia.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The director of the Exposition Universelle, Alfred Picard, thought holding an ancient sport event at the Exposition Universelle was an "absurd anachronism".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] After thanking de Coubertin for his plans, Picard filed them away and nothing more came of it.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A committee was formed for the organization of the Games, consisting of some of the more able sports administrators of the day, and a provisional program was drawn up.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Sports to be included at the games were track and field athletics, swimming, wrestling, gymnastics, fencing, French and British boxing, river and ocean yacht racing, cycling, golf, lifesaving, archery, weightlifting, rowing, diving, and water polo.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] British and Irish sports associations and several influential American universities and sports clubs announced their desire to compete.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Competitors from Russia and Australia also confirmed their intentions to travel to Paris.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] On 9 November 1898, the Union des Sociétés Françaises de Sports Athlétiques ("Union of the French Societies for Athletic Sports" or USFSA) announced that it would have the sole right to any organized sport held during the World's Fair.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] It was an empty threat, but Viscount Charles de La Rochefoucauld, the nominated head of the organizing committee, stepped down rather than be embroiled in the political battle.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC ceded control of the Games to a new committee to oversee every sporting activity connected to the 1900 Exposition Universelle.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Alfred Picard appointed Daniel Mérillon, the head of the French Shooting Association, as president of this organization in February 1899.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Mérillon published an entirely different schedule of events, which resulted in many of those who had made plans to compete with the original program withdrawing and refusing to deal with the new committee.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Between May and October 1900, the new organizing committee held many sporting activities alongside the Paris Exposition.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The press reported competitions variously as "International Championships", "International Games", "Paris Championships", "World Championships" and "Grand Prix of the Paris Exposition".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] These poorly organized games, along with those of 1904, were termed decades later by several historians "The Farcical Games".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Years later, many competitors were unaware that they had competed in the Olympics.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] While there is an Official Report of these Games, complete records of results do not exist.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] De Coubertin commented later to friends, "It's a miracle that the Olympic Movement survived that celebration".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Before July 2021, the IOC had never decided which events were "Olympic".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In fact, Pierre de Coubertin had ceded that entire determination to the organizers.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC webpage for the 1900 Summer Olympics affirms a total of 95 medal events.[note1] Weightlifting and wrestling were dropped since the 1896 Summer Olympics, while 12 new sports were added.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Among the sports below, only croquet was not an international competition, being contested by French players only.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] 14 venues were used at the 1900 Summer Olympics to host 20 sports.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Map of Paris with Olympic venues marked.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Map of France with Olympic venues marked.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The standard of competition at the Games was variable.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Despite a poor-quality track, a strong contingent of top-class American collegiate athletes ensured the track and field competitions were of the highest quality.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The tennis gold medalists were all former Wimbledon champions; swimming and fencing events were of a good standard; and even polo, a minority sport for the social elite, was well represented by some of the best players in the game.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Other sports were noticeably weak in both quality and depth.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Only athletics, swimming and fencing had competitors from more than ten nations.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The history of the archery competition at the 1900 Olympics is one of confusion.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC currently lists six events with Olympic status, but a case has been made that as many as eight other events equally deserve to be considered part of official Olympic history.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] About 150 archers competed in the six events that later had official status conferred.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] However, as many as 5,000 were involved in archery competition in conjunction with the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Belgian Hubert Van Innis took two gold medals and one silver and would add to his tally twenty years later in Antwerp.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The track and field events were held at the home of the Racing Club de France at the Croix-Catelan stadium in Bois de Boulogne.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] No track was laid and races took place on an uneven field of grass littered with trees.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Additional events were held for professionals and a series of handicap races also took place.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] These are not considered official Olympic events.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In the seven events contested over 400 metres or less, the United States took 13 out of a possible 21 medals.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Athletes from Columbia University, Princeton University and the University of Pennsylvania all won gold medals.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Indeed, two would-be dentists from the University of Pennsylvania were among the stars of the Games.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Alvin Kraenzlein won 4 individual gold medals, a feat that has never repeated, while Walter Tewksbury took five medals including two golds.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The hurdles in the 400 m hurdle race were 30-foot (9.1 m)-long telegraph poles arranged on the track and the race, uniquely in Olympic competition, had a water jump on the final straight.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Adolphe Klingelhoeffer, who had Brazilian citizenship in 1900, competed for France in three events.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] United States dominance in sprinting was matched in the longer track races by United Kingdom.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Only George Orton, who won Canada's first Olympic title in the shorter of the two steeplechases, ruined a perfect record for the British.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Orton won his title less than an hour after placing third in the 400-metre hurdles.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The most contentious of all the events in these Games began and ended in the Bois de Boulogne.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Intended to follow the track of the old city wall, the course was poorly marked out and runners often got lost and had to double back on themselves before continuing.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] On some parts of the course, runners had to contend with distractions from cars, bicycles, pedestrians and animals.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Arthur Newton of the United States finished fifth but stated he had not been passed by any other runner during the race.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Another American, Richard Grant, claimed he was run down by a cyclist as he made ground on the leaders.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] French honour seemed to have been satisfied when Michel Théato crossed the finish line and a military band struck up La Marseillaise.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] However, modern research has revealed that Théato was born in Luxembourg and maintained Luxembourgian citizenship throughout his life.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Hungarian discus thrower Rudolf Bauer was the only non-American crowned as Olympic Champion.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] American domination was even greater in the field events than the track events, with outstanding performances coming from Ray Ewry and Irving Baxter.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Ewry started his Olympic career with a sweep of the three standing jumps, while Baxter finished second to Ewry three times and won both the regular high jump and pole vault.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Meyer Prinstein became the first Jewish Olympic gold medalist in the triple jump.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The chistera form of the game was played at this, the sport's only appearance at full Olympic level.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Two pairs entered and the Spanish partnerships of Amezola and Villota became their nations' first Olympic champions.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The mano form of the game and a chistera tournament for professional players were contested unofficially.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] After the withdrawal of teams from the Netherlands and Belgium, only two teams played in the cricket tournament.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A team made up of players from the Albion Cricket Club and the Standard Athletic Club, two Paris clubs consisting almost exclusively of British expatriates, played a touring team from the southwest of England.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Devon and Somerset Wanderers were no more than a team of competent club cricketers (made up from Blundells School old boys and members of Castle Cary Cricket Club), and only Montagu Toller and Alfred Bowerman were deemed good enough to play at county level for Somerset.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The game was played before a small crowd at the Vélodrome de Vincennes.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] An emphatic second innings bowling performance from Toller captured victory for the visitors as time appeared to be running out for them.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] If the French had held out for five more minutes the game would have been a draw.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Knowledge of the game would have been lost but for the forethought of John Symes, a member of the victorious team, who kept a scorecard in his own writing.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The croquet tournament was notable as it marked the first appearance of women at Olympic level.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Madame Desprès, Madame Filleul-Brohy and Mademoiselle Ohier were eliminated in the first round of competition.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A single paying spectator attended the tournament, an elderly English gentleman who travelled from Nice for the early stages.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] An unofficial two-ball handicap competition was also held.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] This was also the only Olympiad where croquet was part of the official programme, though there was the variant called roque at the 1904 Summer Olympics.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The home nation won six of the nine medals available, including one that was initially awarded to Great Britain until this was reversed in 2024.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A number of unofficial events were held for both amateurs and professionals.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Equestrian sport made its debut at the Olympic Games with three jumping events being held, plus two other events.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Italian rider Gian Giorgio Trissino won a gold and a silver.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] He narrowly missed making Olympic history by winning two medals in the same event.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Competing with two different horses in the high jump, he jointly won the gold medal and finished in 4th place on his second horse.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Nineteen nations were represented in the fencing competition, which was held in a field near the cutlery exhibit at the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] French fencers dominated the proceedings but both Cuba and Italy also took titles.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The early rounds of the foil competitions were judged on style rather than the actual result of the contest.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] This meant that some fencers were eliminated without losing a contest while others were defeated and still progressed to the next rounds.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The first football champions at the Olympics were the London amateurs of Upton Park F.C.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A crowd of around 500 spectators saw them defeat their French rivals.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Margaret Ives Abbott, a student of art from Chicago, played in and won a nine-hole golf tournament on an October Tuesday in Paris.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] She died in 1955 without being aware that the tournament was part of the Olympic Games and she had become America's first ever female Olympic champion.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] 135 gymnasts took part in a competition that involved elements from track and field and weightlifting as well as gymnastic disciplines.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Eight separate tournaments were held in 1900 as part of the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Only the Grand Prix Internationale de l'Exposition is counted as an official medal event.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Entries were from clubs rather than countries, and the winning Foxhunters club comprised English, Irish and American players.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Mexico won its first medal in this sport, a bronze won by Guillermo Hayden Wright, Marquez de Villavieja and three brothers: Eustaquio de Escandón y Barron, Pablo de Escandón y Barron and Manuel de Escandón y Barron.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Competitions were held on the River Seine.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Following this, officials decided to run another final for the boycotting crews.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Both events are considered official Olympic competitions.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In a number of events, crews saw the advantage of having ultra-lightweight coxswains and recruited local boys for race days.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Most of these remain a mystery; some could have been under ten years old.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Three teams competed in the Rugby tournament.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A French representative team defeated a team from the German city of Frankfurt and Moseley Wanderers from England.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Moseley team had played a full game of rugby in England the day before they made the journey to Paris.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] They arrived in the morning, played the match in the afternoon and were back in their home country by the next morning.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The proposed game between the British and German sides was cancelled, and both are credited as silver medalists.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Franco-Haitian centre Constantin Henriquez become the first black gold medalist.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 sailing regatta differs from every other Olympic regatta in a number of ways.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In most classes, there were two distinct "finals", boats were assigned time handicaps according to their weight within each class and cash prizes were handed out to the winner of each race.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC initially recognized the winner of the first race in each class as Olympic champion except in the case of the 10-20 ton class, which was decided on aggregate time over three races.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] However currently the participants of both first and second races in 3 classes (0-0.5t, 1-2t and 2-3t) are present in the as medalists, so the second races in these 3 classes were recognized by the IOC, as recommended by Olympic historian Bill Mallon.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] To support the recognition of a total of 95 medal events per Mallon's suggestion, one more race in each of 2 other classes (0.5-1t and 3-10t) has been recognized by the IOC.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Thus, for five of the eight events, two gold, two silver and two bronze medals were retrospectively awarded.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Races were held at both Meulan and Le Havre and medals shared among five nations.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] France and Great Britain were the most successful of the countries involved.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A number of people named as members of medal-winning crews by the IOC have been proved not to have competed; others have their participation seriously questioned by historical research.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Switzerland's Konrad Stäheli was the outstanding marksman of the Games, taking a trio of titles and leading his country to the top of the shooting medal table.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The medals were shared between six different nations.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] There is a debate as to whether the live pigeon shooting event was a full Olympic event, Belgian Leon Lunden shot twenty-one birds on his way to the championship.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Up to thirty unofficial shooting events were also held, most involving professional marksmen.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Research has shown that one of the medal events in the IOC database (25m rapid fire pistol, also called military pistol cat.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The muddied waters of the Seine hosted the swimming events in 1900.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Run with the current, the races produced very fast times by the standards of the day.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] John Arthur Jarvis of Great Britain, Frederick Lane of Australia and the German Ernst Hoppenberg each won two titles.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Lane received a 50-pound bronze statue of a horse as a prize.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The obstacle race required both swimming underneath and climbing over rows of boats while Charles de Venville stayed submerged for over a minute to win the underwater swimming event.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A high-quality men's tournament saw three past or future Wimbledon champions reach the semi-finals.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Laurence Doherty reached the final when older brother Reggie stepped aside and let his sibling advance to the final.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The two refused to play each other in what they considered a minor tournament.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] On the 11th of July a landmark was reached in the history of the Olympic Games.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Charlotte Cooper, already three times Wimbledon champion, took the singles championship to become the first individual female Olympic champion, also winning the mixed doubles event.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A combined Sweden/Denmark team, made up of three competitors from each country, defeated the French team to win the title.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] One of the members of the French team was a Colombian citizen.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] They were left as the only participating teams; the United States had entered but were forced to scratch as three of their team were involved in the final of the hammer.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Edgar Aabye was a journalist covering the Games for the Danish newspaper Politiken and was asked to join the team when another puller was taken ill.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Osborne Swimming Club, representing Great Britain, were unchallenged in the tournament, scoring 29 goals and conceding only 3 in their 3 matches.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In the final, they limited the number of shots on goal to avoid humiliating their opponents.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] One of its team members, Victor Lindberg, was from New Zealand, while Thomas William Burgess of the bronze medal-winning Libellule de Paris team represented Great Britain in the swimming events.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 Games were not governed by a specific Olympic organizing committee, but were instead held as an appendage to the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] An enormous number of events was held, though many fall short of the standards later required for Olympic championship status.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] After the several initial editions of the Olympic Games, decisions as to which Olympic events were termed "official" and which had "unofficial" or "demonstration" status were usually left to the Olympic organizing committees and/or the IOC.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In the early Olympic Games, however, no decision as to the official status of any event was made at the time of the Games.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] While a document from 1912 exists, listing results from the 1900 Games, and formed the original basis of the results of the Paris games in the IOC database, the reliability and authenticity of this paper has been questioned by Olympic historians.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Further complicating matters, the IOC has never determined which events were Olympic and which were not.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Of the three events that satisfied three criteria, only croquet has been accorded Olympic status.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In this regard, one of the ten croquet players, Marcel Haëntjens, had been believed to be Belgian, and the croquet events were thus considered as international.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Despite the Flemish name, it was discovered in recent times that Haëntjens was French.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Scholastic and military events were also held across a range of sports.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Four planned competitions were not organized due to a lack of participants: balle au tamis, field hockey, jeu de paume and lacrosse.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] According to the International Olympic Committee, 26 nations sent competitors to this edition.[note1] The concept of "national teams" chosen by National Olympic Committees did not exist at this point in time.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] When counting the number of participating countries in the early Olympic Games, the IOC does not take into account otherwise unrepresented countries whose citizens competed for other countries.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Modern research shows that at the 1900 Olympics, the athletes of at least four otherwise unrepresented countries competed for other countries in both individual and team sports.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] George Orton, gold medalist in 2500 metres steeplechase event and bronze medalist in 400 metres hurdles event, and Ronald J.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] MacDonald, both of Canada, competed for the U.S. athletics team.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Orton ran for the University of Pennsylvania and was therefore assumed to be American, but he always considered himself a Canadian.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Michel Théato, the winner of the marathon, competed for the French athletics team.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] He was a Luxembourger; however, this was only discovered decades later.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Francisco Henríquez de Zubiría of Colombia was a silver medal-winner on the French tug of war team.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Victor Lindberg of New Zealand was a gold medal-winner on the British water polo team.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC website lists all of them in the results section under their nationalities, but does not include their countries among the 26 participating countries.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Debuting nations at the games included Argentina, Belgium, Bohemia, Cuba, Haiti, India, Mexico, Netherlands, Norway, Persia, Peru, Romania, Russia and Spain.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Nations that participated in the previous games in Athens 1896 but were absent in Paris 1900 included Bulgaria and Chile.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Austria and Hungary competed as two sovereign countries.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The polity known as Austria-Hungary is mistakenly considered a single sovereign country, while in reality was two sovereign states in real union with a single monarch who was titled both emperor of Austria and king of Hungary.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] At the time, Bohemia was part of Austria, while Australia, Canada and India were all part of the British Empire.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Algeria sent four gymnasts who competed for France, while all of Ireland was considered a part of Great Britain: Irish athletes competed in athletics, polo, sailing and tennis.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Further, a Polish fencer represented Russia, a Croatian fencer represented Austria, and two Slovak athletes competed for Hungary.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The concept of "national teams" chosen by National Olympic Committees did not exist at this point in time.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 Olympics is unique in being the only Olympic Games to feature rectangular medals, which were designed by Frédérique Vernon.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Gilt silver medals were awarded for 1st place in shooting, lifesaving, automobile racing and gymnastics.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Whilst 2nd place silver medals were awarded in shooting, rowing, yachting, tennis, gymnastics, sabre, fencing, equestrian and athletics.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] With 3rd place bronze medals being awarded in gymnastics, firefighting and shooting.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In many sports, however, medals were not awarded.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] With most of the listed prizes were cups and other similar trophies.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee has retrospectively assigned gold, silver and bronze medals to all competitors who earned 1st, 2nd and 3rd-place finishes, respectively, in order to bring early Olympics in line with current awards.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] For the first Olympic Games (until Antwerp in 1920), it is difficult to give the exact number of medals awarded to some countries, due to the fact that teams were composed of athletes from different countries.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] For Olympic Games before 1908 there is no universally accepted definition of nationality, and medal tables may vary depending on the chosen definition.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] For example, Australian Stanley Rowley competed as part of a team selected by the Amateur Athletic Association of England.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1900 Games.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The **1904 Summer Olympics** (officially the **Games of the III Olympiad** and also known as **St.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis 1904**) were an international multi-sport event held in St.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis, Missouri, United States, from 1 July to 23 November 1904.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Many events were conducted at what is now known as Francis Field on the campus of Washington University in St.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] This was the first time that the Olympic Games were held outside Europe.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Tensions caused by the Russo–Japanese War and difficulties in traveling to St.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis resulted in very few top-class athletes from outside the United States and Canada taking part in the 1904 Games.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Only 69–74 of the 651 athletes who competed came from outside North America, and only between 12 and 15 nations were represented in all.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Some events subsequently combined the U.S. national championship with the Olympic championship.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The current three-medal format of gold, silver and bronze for first, second and third place was introduced at the 1904 Olympics.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] After the first two editions of the Olympic Games were awarded to Athens and Paris, the IOC's first open bidding process was held for the 1904 Olympics at the 4th IOC Session in Paris in May 1901.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Chicago civic leaders, including University of Chicago president William Rainey Harper, formed the International Olympian Games Association in February 1901 to plan for hosting the Olympics.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Shortly before the session began, another American bid was submitted from St.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis, which was then preparing to host the Louisiana Purchase Exposition, a World's Fair in 1903.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] At the session, representatives of Chicago offered to put $100,000 (equivalent to $3,870,000 in 2025) toward the games.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Unable to compete with this, all other countries withdrew their bids before the IOC voted; cities which had previously expressed interest in the 1904 games included Berlin, Copenhagen, and Stockholm.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The IOC delegates then voted between the choices of Chicago and St.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis, with Chicago winning unanimously on May 21.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis was forced to postpone its World's Fair from 1903 to 1904, it began planning athletic events that would compete directly with the Olympics in Chicago.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis and planned to hold its national championships at the World's Fair.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] In the meantime, Chicago's plans for a new stadium on the shore of Lake Michigan seating 75,000 met considerable opposition from local leaders, including Aaron Montgomery Ward, putting the centerpiece of Chicago's Olympic bid into question.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] On December 23, 1902, fearing that the dispute would permanently damage the Olympic movement, the IOC asked its members to approve, by a postal vote, the transfer of the Olympic Games to St.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] When the votes were tallied, IOC founder Pierre de Coubertin telegraphed the Chicago committee on February 10, 1903, to inform them that the Games had been moved.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Boxing, dumbbells, catch wrestling (which later became freestyle wrestling), and the decathlon made their debuts.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The swimming events were held in a temporary pond near Skinker and Wydown Boulevards, where "lifesaving demonstrations" of unsinkable lifeboats for ocean liners took place.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Chicago runner James Lightbody won the steeplechase and the 800 m and then set a natural world record in the 1500 m.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Harry Hillman won both the 200 m and 400 m hurdles and also the flat 400 m.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Sprinter Archie Hahn was champion in the 60 m, 100 m and 200 m.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] In this last race, he set an Olympic record in 21.6, a natural record that stood for 28 years.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] In the discus, after American Martin Sheridan had thrown exactly the same distance as his compatriot, Ralph Rose (39.28 m), the judges gave them both an extra throw to decide the winner.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Sheridan won the decider and claimed the gold medal.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Ray Ewry again won all three standing jumps.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The team representing Great Britain was awarded a total of two medals, both won by Irish athletes.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The top non-U.S. athlete was Emil Rausch of Germany, who won three swimming events.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Zoltán Halmay of Hungary and Charles Daniels of the United States each won two swimming gold medals.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Galt Football Club from Canada won the gold medal in football.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The organizers of the World's Fair held "Anthropology Days" on August 12 and 13.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Since the 1889 Paris Exposition, human zoos, as a key feature of world's fairs, functioned as demonstrations of anthropological notions of race, progress, and civilization.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] These goals were followed also at the 1904 World's Fair.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Fourteen hundred indigenous people from Southeast Asia, the Pacific Islands, East Asia, Africa, the Middle East, South America and North America were displayed in anthropological exhibits that showed them in their natural habitats.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Another 1600 indigenous people displayed their culture in other areas of the Louisiana Purchase Exposition (LPE), including on the fairgrounds and at the Model School, where American Indian boarding schools students demonstrated their successful assimilation.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The sporting event itself took place with the participation of about 100 paid indigenous men.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Contests included "baseball throwing, shot put, running, broad jumping, weight lifting, pole climbing, and tugs-of-war before a crowd of approximately ten thousand".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] No women participated in Anthropology Days, though some, notably the Fort Shaw Indian School girls basketball team, did compete in other athletic events at the LPE.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] According to theorist Susan Brownell, world's fairs – with their inclusion of human zoos – and the Olympics were a logical fit at this time, as they "were both linked to an underlying cultural logic that gave them a natural affinity".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Also, one of the original intentions of Anthropology Days was to create publicity for the official Olympic events.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The 1904 Summer Olympic program featured 16 sports encompassing 95 events in 18 disciplines.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Swimming, diving and water polo are considered three disciplines of the same sport, *aquatics*.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] In July 2021 the IOC accepted the recommendation of Olympic historian Bill Mallon regarding which sports and events should be considered as Olympic.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Boxing made its Olympic debut at the St.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The sport has since featured at every Summer Olympics, except for the 1912 Stockholm Games.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] While wrestling made a return, it was exclusively the newly debuted catch wrestling (which later became freestyle wrestling) as opposed to Greco-Roman style of the 1896 Summer Olympics.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Five nations were represented, with each of the 42 competitors having resided in the United States.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Later editions would have both styles of wrestling in their programs.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Basketball, hurling, American football and Gaelic football were featured as unofficial sports.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] There was a demonstration bout of women's boxing.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Baseball is also noted by the World Baseball Softball Confederation to have appeared at the Games, though it does not appear in the list compiled by Olympic historian Bill Mallon and any results are not known.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Creve Coeur Lake is located further west.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Five sports venues were used for the 1904 Summer Olympics.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The venues included Glen Echo Country Club, the first golf course constructed west of the Mississippi River, which had opened in 1901.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Three Olympic sports were hosted at Forest Park, the site of the Louisiana Purchase Exposition which was being held concurrently with the Olympics: the Life Saving Exhibition Lake at Forest Park was used for the diving, swimming, and water polo events.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Creve Coeur Lake became the first park of St.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The Lake has hosted rowing regattas since 1882 and still hosts them as of 2010.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Francis Olympic Field and Gymnasium are still in use on the Washington University in St.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] An ornamental gate commemorating the 1904 Games was constructed outside the stadium immediately after the Exposition.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] A swimming pool was added to the gymnasium in 1985.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Forest Park, constructed in 1876, is still in use as of 2021 and attracts over 12 million visitors annually.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Glen Echo Country Club remains in use as a golf course today as of 2021.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Athletes from thirteen nations competed in St.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Numbers in parentheses indicate the number of known competitors for each nation.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis in 1904, and European tensions caused by the Russo-Japanese War, only 69–74 athletes from outside North America participated in the Olympics.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] These are the nations that won medals at the 1904 Games.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The nationalities of some medalists were disputed, as many American athletes were recent immigrants to the United States who had not yet been granted U.S. citizenship.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] These cases saw medals credited to the United States transferred to other countries or mixed teams.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] In addition, the IOC had counted one gold, one silver, and two bronze medals won by the American fencer Albertson Van Zo Post for Cuba instead of the United States.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The IOC also had shown Charles Tatham as a Cuban medal-winner for individual fencing events (foil and épée) and American silver medalist in the team foil event, but he was an American.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] All are now credited to the United States.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The **1906 Intercalated Games** or **1906 Olympic Games** (Greek: Μεσολυμπιάδα, romanized: *Mesolympiada*, lit.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] 'Mesolympics'), held from 22 April 1906 to 2 May 1906, was an international multi-sport event that was celebrated in Athens, Greece.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] It was at the time considered to be part of the series of the Olympic Games, and was referred to as the "Second International Olympic Games in Athens" by the International Olympic Committee (IOC).
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The 1906 Games is noted for its influence on the Olympic tradition and the records broken during these Games are recorded in history, but are no longer considered part of the Olympic records.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] 894 athletes from 20 nations competed in this competition.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The idea behind the Intercalated Games was to have an Olympics in Greece every four years, but this would be the first and last.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The idea was not pursued further, and is sometimes termed the "forgotten Games" in the context of the Olympics.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The next Olympic Games was the 1908 Summer Olympics in London; the next time the Olympic Games returned to Greece was 98 years later in 2004, also in Athens.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The Intercalated Olympic Games were to be a series of *International Olympic Games* halfway between what is now known as the Games of the Olympiad, old and new.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] This proposed series of Games, intercalated in the Olympic Games cycle, was always to be held in Athens and was to have equal status with the international Games.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] However, the only such Games was held in 1906.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] One reason for the Games in 1906 was to celebrate the tenth anniversary of the 1896 Games.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The first Intercalated Games had been scheduled by the International Olympic Committee in 1901 as part of a new schedule, where every four years, in between the internationally organised Games, there would be an Intermediate Games held in Athens.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] This was a compromise; after the successful Games of Athens 1896, the Greeks suggested they could organise the Games every four years.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] Since they had the accommodation and had proven they could hold well-organised Games, they received substantial public support.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] However, Pierre de Coubertin, the founder of the International Olympic Committee, opposed this, as he had intended for the first Games to be in Paris in 1900.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] After Paris had lost the première Olympics, De Coubertin did not want the Games to be permanently hosted elsewhere.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The 1900 Games were overshadowed by the Exposition Universelle, whose organising committee disagreed with De Coubertin's ideas to such an extent that he resigned.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The organisation of the 1900 Games was haphazard by today's standards, and although some events, such as archery, drew widespread attention, many others were poorly attended.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] Historians' opinions still differ over which events should be considered "Olympic".
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] Consequently, the IOC supported the Greek idea by granting them a second series of quadrennial Games in between the first series.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] This was a departure from the ancient schedule, but it was expected that, if the ancient Greeks could keep a four-year schedule, the modern Olympic Movement could keep a two-year schedule.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] As 1902 was now too close to be logistically workable, and Greece was experiencing political and economic difficulties, the 2nd Olympic Games in Athens were scheduled for 1906, and the IOC as a whole gave Greece full support for the organisation.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] Louis, Missouri were overshadowed by the Louisiana Purchase Exposition, and their organisation was even worse than that of Paris 1900, while travel difficulties meant that only 20% of the athletes were non-American; of these, half were Canadian.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] It was clear the Olympic Movement was in a dire situation and desperately needed to recapture the spirit of Athens 1896.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] It also needed to do so quickly, as to those who did not participate in St.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] Louis, 1908 was a gap of eight years, by which time there would be little, if any, goodwill left for the Games.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] To make matters worse, Rome, the proposed host for 1908, was also planning an exhibition at the same time as the Games, which had been responsible for the failures of Paris and St.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] To the IOC, the 1906 Athens Games being just around the corner would have been a lifeline.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] While De Coubertin still opposed the idea and did not do anything more than his function required of him, the IOC as a whole gave the Greek organising committee full support for the organisation.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] These games offered Greece the huge opportunity to show that it was important to Europe's present and its past.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] It is clear from the beginning that the Olympic Games 1906 became "a grand project far beyond the status of a mere sports meeting", with new structures built to accommodate the events including the restoration of the ancient stadium in Athens.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The 1906 Games were quite successful: unlike the Games of 1900, 1904 or 1908, they were not stretched out over several months, and unlike 1900 and 1904, they were not overshadowed by an international exposition.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] Their crisp implementation was most likely instrumental in the continued existence of the Games.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] These, along with various other changes, are now accepted as tradition.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The Games were held from 22 April to 2 May 1906, in Athens, Greece.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] They took place in the Panathenaic Stadium, which had already hosted the 1896 Games and the earlier Zappas Olympics of 1870 and 1875.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The Games excluded several disciplines that had occurred during the past two Games; it was unclear whether they ought to have been part of the Olympic Games.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] Added to the program were the javelin throw and the pentathlon.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The 1906 Games is noted for its opening and closing ceremonies, which initiated this tradition.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The 1908 Games introduced the tradition of the host coming in as the last in the parade also.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] These were the first Games to include an opening ceremony with athletes marching into the stadium as national teams behind their flags.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] King George I officially opened the Games.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] Six thousand schoolchildren took part in the first ever Olympic closing ceremony.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] 854 athletes, 848 men and six women, from 20 countries, competed at the 1906 Intercalated Games.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] 78 events in 14 disciplines, comprising 12 sports, were part of the 1906 Games.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] These medals were distributed but are no longer recognized by the International Olympic Committee.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1948-summer-olympics] The **1948 Summer Olympics**, officially the **Games of the XIV Olympiad** and officially branded as **London 1948**, were an international multi-sport event held from 29 July to 14 August 1948 in London, United Kingdom.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1948-summer-olympics] Following a twelve-year hiatus caused by the outbreak of World War II, these were the first Summer Olympics held since the 1936 Games in Berlin.
[src:1948-summer-olympics/1948-summer-olympics] The 1940 Olympic Games had been scheduled for Tokyo and then for Helsinki, while the 1944 Olympic Games had been provisionally planned for London.
